{"title_page": "Qalansawe", "text_new": "{{Infobox Israel municipality\n| name = Qalansawe\n| image_skyline = Qalansuwa-541.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| emblem = Qalansawe COA.png\n| emblem_type = Emblem of Qalansawe\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05e1\u05d5\u05d5\u05d4}}\n| ISO = Qalansuwa\n| arname = \u0642\u0644\u0646\u0633\u0648\u0629\n| meaning = \n| founded = \n| type = city\n| typefrom = \n| stdHeb = Kalansuwa or Qalansuwa\n| altUnoSp = Kalansoueh,<ref name = Guerinp350>Guerin, 1875, [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr04gugoog#page/n375/mode/1up p. 350]</ref> Qalansuwa\n| country = israel\n| district = center\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Qalansawe}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n| area_dunam = 8400\n| mayor = Abdulbast Salameh\n| pushpin_map = Israel center ta#Israel| pushpin_label_position=left\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|16|56.34|N|34|59|0.27|E|region:IL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| palgrid = 148/187\n| ITMgrid = 198600/687800 \n}}\n\n'''Qalansawe''' or '''Qalansuwa''' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u0644\u0646\u0633\u0648\u0629}}, {{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05e1\u05d5\u05d5\u05d4}}, lit. \"turban\")<ref>[http://qa.sunnipath.com/issue_view.asp?HD=7&ID=14264&CATE=1 The turban tradition in Islam]</ref><ref>Palmer, 1881, p.[https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp00conduoft#page/187/mode/1up 187]</ref> is a city in the [[Central District (Israel)|Central District]] of [[Israel]]. Part of [[Triangle (Israel)|the Triangle]], in {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Qalansawe}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Qalansuwa-531.jpg|thumb|250px|Mosque built on Crusader ruins]]\nDuring the [[Abbasid Revolution]] in 750, which toppled the [[Umayyad Caliphate]], numerous members of the [[Umayyad dynasty]] were deported to Qalansawe from Egypt for execution, including descendants of caliphs [[Umar II]] ({{reign|717|720}}) and [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|715|717}}).<ref>Robinson 2010, p. 240.</ref> From the ninth century until the Crusader times, Qalansawe was a stop on the [[Cairo]]-[[Damascus]] road, between [[Lajjun]] and [[Ramla]].<ref>Petersen, 2001, pp. [https://www.academia.edu/21620056/Gazetteer_5_K-R 248-249], citing among others Hartmann, 1910, [http://menadoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/dmg/periodical/pageview/56952 675], [http://menadoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/dmg/periodical/pageview/56953 676]</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Crusades|Crusader]] period, the village was known as ''Calanson'', ''Calansue'', ''Calanzon'' or ''Kalensue''.<ref name=\"Pringle\">Pringle, 1997, pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=-_NbE5obqRMC&pg=PA77 77]\u2013[https://books.google.com/books?id=-_NbE5obqRMC&pg=PA78 78]</ref> In 1128, it was given to the [[Hospitaller]]s by the knight Godfrey of Flujeac.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/><ref>R\u00f6hricht, 1904,  RRH Ad, pp.[https://archive.org/stream/registaregnihier00rhuoft#page/9/mode/1up 9]-10, No. 121a</ref> [[Yaqut al-Hamawi|Yaqut]] (\u20201229) wrote that Qalansawe, Castle of the Plans, of the Crusaders, was a [[fortress]] near Ramle. He adds that \"many of the [[Omayyads]] were slain there.\"<ref>Cited in Le Strange, 1890, p.[https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/476/mode/1up 476]</ref> Remnants of a crusader fortress remain today.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/> It remained in Hospitallers hands (except for 1187\u20131191) until [[Baybars]] took it in 1265.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/> However, during this period the lord of [[Caesarea]] appears to have retained overlordship.<ref name=\"Pringle\"/>\n\nIn 1265, after the [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]]s had defeated the [[Crusades|Crusaders]], Qalansawe was mentioned among the estates which Sultan [[Baibars]] granted his followers. It was divided equally between two of his  [[Emir#Military ranks and titles|emir]]s: '''Izz al-Din Aidamur al-Halabi al-Salihi'' and ''Shams al-Din Sunqur al-Rumi al-Salihi''.<ref>[[Ibn al-Furat]], 1971, pp. 8o, 210, 249 (map)</ref>\n\n===Ottoman period===\nIn 1517,  the village was included in the [[Ottoman Syria|Ottoman Empire]] with the rest of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], and in the  1596 [[daftar|tax-records]] it appeared located  in  the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Bani Sa'b of the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|Liwa]]'' of [[Sanjak of Nablus|Nablus]]. It had a population of 29 [[Muslim]] households. They paid a fixed tax-rate of 33.3% on agricultural products, including wheat, barley, summer crops, olives, goats or beehives, and a press for olives or grapes; a total of 11,342  [[ak\u00e7e]].<ref>H\u00fctteroth and  Abdulfattah, 1977, p. 139</ref> [[Pierre Jacotin]] called the village ''Qalensawi'' on his map from 1799.<ref>Karmon, 1960, p. [http://www.jchp.ucla.edu/Bibliography/Karmon,_Y_1960_Jacotin_Map_(IEJ_10).pdf 170] Note that Karmon gives the wrong grid-numbers for Qalansawe</ref>\n\nIn 1870 the French explorer [[Victor Gu\u00e9rin]] found it to have 500 inhabitants.<ref name=Guerinp350/> He then \"examined the remains of a beautiful church, built east and west, and divided into three [[naves]], terminating to the east in three [[apse]]s. It was formerly constructed of good cut stones, some of which were slightly embossed, as is proved by the portions still standing. The naves were separated one from the other by monolithic [[columns]], only the positions of which can be traced. They were probably crowned by [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]] [[Capital (architecture)#Classical capital|capitals]], for I found one in a house, of white marble, cut into a mortar by the inhabitants, who told me they brought it from the site of the church. The other capitals and shafts had disappeared. Probably they came from some more ancient building. An elegant door, with pointed arch, is still standing. Under the nave runs a [[vaulted]] crypt, now divided into several compartments, which serve as a shelter for as many families. The good walls seem ancient. One of these is near the church; the other below the village. The latter is large, and surmounted by a vaulted [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] in cut stones.\"<ref>Gu\u00e9rin, 1875, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr04gugoog#page/n375/mode/1up 350]-352, [https://archive.org/stream/descriptiongogr04gugoog#page/n379/mode/1up 354] as translated in Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/201/mode/1up 201]</ref>\n\nIn 1882, the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s ''Survey of Western Palestine'' described it as being of moderate size, and the seat of a [[Caimacam]]. In the centre of the village was a Crusader tower and hall, surrounded by the village houses, mostly made of [[adobe]]. Wells and a spring to the west supplied water.<ref>Conder and Kitchener, 1882, SWP II, p. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/165/mode/1up 165]</ref>\n\n===British Mandate of Palestine period===\nIn the [[1922 census of Palestine]] conducted by the [[British Mandate for Palestine (legal instrument)|British Mandate authorities]], Qualansawe had a population of 871 Muslims,<ref name=\"Census1922\">Barron, 1923,  Table IX, Sub-district of Tulkarem, p. [https://archive.org/stream/PalestineCensus1922/Palestine%20Census%20%281922%29#page/n30/mode/1up  28]</ref> increasing in the [[1931 census of Palestine|1931 census]]  to 1069, still all Muslim, in a total of 225 houses.<ref name=\"Census1931\">Mills, 1932, p. [https://archive.org/details/CensusOfPalestine1931.PopulationOfVillagesTownsAndAdministrativeAreas 56]</ref>\n\nBy the [[Village Statistics, 1945|1945 statistics]], the village had 1540 Muslim inhabitants,<ref name=DoS1945>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics, 1945,  p. [http://users.cecs.anu.edu.au/~bdm/yabber/census/VSpages/VS1945_p21.jpg 21]</ref> who owned a total of owned 17,249 [[dunam]]s of land.<ref name=Hadawi40>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945''. Quoted in  Hadawi, 1970 p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20I/Tulkarm/Page-076.jpg 76]</ref> 473  dunams were  for [[citrus]] and [[bananas]], 759 plantations and irrigable land, 15,936  for cereals,<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi, 1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20II/Tulkarm/Page-127.jpg   127]</ref> while 47 dunams were built-up (urban) land.<ref>Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics. ''Village Statistics, April, 1945.'' Quoted in Hadawi,  1970, p. [http://www.palestineremembered.com/download/VillageStatistics/Table%20III/Tulkarm/Page-177.jpg    177]</ref>\n\n[[File:Qalansawe 1942.jpg|thumb|Qalansawe 1942 1:20,000]]\n[[File:Tulkarm 1945.jpg|thumb|Qalansawe (Qalansuwa) 1945 1:250,000]]\n\n===1948, and after===\nDuring the [[1948 Palestine war]], Jewish forces had decided to \"conquer and destroy\" or later \"expel or subdue\" Qalansawe,<ref>Morris, 2004, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uM_kFX6edX8C&pg=PA246 246]</ref> but the village was not taken<ref>Morris, 2004, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uM_kFX6edX8C&pg=PA302 302]</ref> and was only transferred to Israeli sovereignty in May 1949 as part of the  [[1949 Armistice Agreements#With Jordan|Israel-Jordan armistice agreement]].<ref name=UN1949>[http://domino.un.org/unispal.nsf/9a798adbf322aff38525617b006d88d7/f03d55e48f77ab698525643b00608d34 UN Doc S/1302/Rev.1 of 3 April 1949] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612045743/http://domino.un.org/unispal.nsf/9a798adbf322aff38525617b006d88d7/f03d55e48f77ab698525643b00608d34 |date=12 June 2012 }}</ref> Political considerations then prevented the expulsion of the villagers.<ref>Morris, 2004, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uM_kFX6edX8C&pg=PA531 531]</ref>\n\nBy 1962, land ownership had dropped to 6,620 dunams, mostly due to expropriation of land by the Israeli government in 1953\u20131954.<ref>{{cite journal | author = [[Sabri Jiryis|S. Jiryis]] | title = The land question in Israel | journal = MERIP Reports | volume = No. 37 | year = 1976 | pages = 5\u201320, 24\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, the Israeli government demolished 11 buildings being built by 4 families, on the grounds that they were built without permits.<ref name=Haaretz1>{{cite news | title = Israel Demolishes Buildings in Arab Town, Citing Lack of Permits | url = http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-1.764274 | author = Jack Khoury | date = Jan 10, 2017 | newspaper = Haaretz}}</ref> The families were given two days notice, which they said was insufficient for any legal response.<ref name=Haaretz1/> The mayor of Qalansawe, who announced his resignation, said that he had fought unsuccessfully for years for an expansion of the town's building plan, forcing the residents to build on agricultural land.<ref name=Haaretz2>{{cite news | title = Thousands Rally in Israeli Arab Town After State Demolishes Homes | url = http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-1.764896 | author = Jack Khoury | date = Jan 13, 2017 | newspaper = Haaretz}}</ref> Thousands of people rallied in support of the village and a one-day strike was called.<ref name=Haaretz2/><ref>{{cite news | title = Israeli Arabs strike in protest at house demolitions | url =  http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/afp/2017/01/israel-arabs-demolitions-strike.html | newspaper = Al-Monitor | author = AFP | author-link = Agence France-Presse | date = January 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2001, the ethnic makeup of the city was virtually all [[Arab]] [[Muslim]]s without significant [[Jew]]ish population. There were 7,700 males and 7,300 females. 53.2% of the residents were 19 years of age or younger, 17.1% were between 20 and 29, 17.9% between 30 and 44, 8.0% from 45 to 59, 1.6% from 60 to 64, and 2.2% 65 years of age or older. The population growth rate in 2001 was 3.5%.\n\nDue to marriages among relatives, the residents suffer from a high percentage of genetic diseases, especially [[hearing impairment]].<ref name=\"knesset-mmm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.knesset.gov.il/MMM/data/docs/m00084.rtf|title=Close Family Marriages and Polygamy|publisher=[[Knesset]]|format=RTF|accessdate=2008-07-26|date=2001-03-19|author=Warzberger, Rachel|language=he}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arab localities in Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book | editor =Barron,  J.B. | title = Palestine: Report and General Abstracts of the Census of 1922 |url=https://archive.org/details/PalestineCensus1922 |publisher = Government of Palestine | year = 1923}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Conder|first1=C.R.|authorlink1=Claude Reignier Conder|last2=Kitchener|first2=H.H.|authorlink2=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|year=1882|url=https://archive.org/details/surveyofwesternp02conduoft|title=The Survey of Western Palestine: Memoirs of the Topography, Orography, Hydrography, and Archaeology|location=London|publisher=[[Palestine Exploration Fund|Committee of the Palestine Exploration Fund]]|volume=2}}  (pp. [https://archive.org/stream/surveyofwesternp02conduoft#page/199/mode/1up 199]-201.)\n*{{cite  book|url=http://publishing.cdlib.org/ucpressebooks/view?docId=ft896nb5pc&chunk.id=s2.1.2&toc.depth=1&toc.id=s1.1.5&brand=eschol|title=Rediscovering Palestine, Merchants and Peasants in Jabal Nablus, 1700\u20131900|accessdate=2011-11-07|last=Doumani |first=B.|authorlink= Beshara Doumani|year=1995|publisher=University of California Press|postscript=<!--None-->}} p.&nbsp;19\n*{{cite book|title=Village Statistics, April, 1945 |url=http://web.nli.org.il/sites/nli/Hebrew/library/Pages/BookReader.aspx?pid=856390|author=Government of Palestine, Department of Statistics|year=1945|publisher= }}  \n*{{cite book|last=Gu\u00e9rin|first=V.|authorlink=Victor Gu\u00e9rin|title=Description G\u00e9ographique  Historique et Arch\u00e9ologique de