{"title_page": "Brominated flame retardant", "text_new": "'''Brominated flame retardants''' ('''BFRs''') are [[organobromine compound]]s that have an inhibitory effect on combustion chemistry and tend to reduce the flammability of products containing them. The brominated variety of commercialized chemical flame retardants comprise approximately 19.7% of the market. They are effective in plastics and textile applications like electronics, clothes and furniture.\n\n==Types of compounds==\nMany different BFRs are produced [[organic synthesis|synthetically]] with widely varying chemical properties. There are several groups:<ref>Michael J. Dagani, Henry J. Barda, Theodore J. Benya, David C. Sanders \"Bromine Compounds\" Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 2002, Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.  {{DOI|10.1002/14356007.a04_405}}</ref>\n\n* [[Polybrominated diphenyl ethers]] (PBDEs): [[DecaBDE]], [[OctaBDE]] (not manufactured anymore), [[PentaBDE]] (not manufactured anymore, the first BFR, commercialized in the 1950s)\n* [[Polybrominated biphenyl]] (PBB), not manufactured anymore\n* Brominated cyclohydrocarbons\n* Other brominated flame retardants with different properties and mechanisms\n\n[[Decabromodiphenyl ether]] (''Deca-BDE'' or ''DeBDE'') - In August 2012, the UK authorities proposed decabromodiphenyl ether (Deca-BDE or DeBDE) as a candidate for Authorisation under the EU\u2018s regulatory regime on chemicals, REACH. On 5 July 2013 [[ECHA]] withdrew Deca-BDE from its list of priority substances for Authorisation under REACH, therefore closing the public consultation. On 1 August 2014, ECHA submitted a restriction proposal for Deca-BDE. The agency is proposing a restriction on the manufacture, use and placing on the market of the substance and of mixtures and articles containing it. On 17 September 2014, ECHA submitted the restriction report which initiates a six months public consultation. On 9 February 2017, the [[European Commission]] adopted Regulation EU 2017/227. Article 1 of this regulation states that Regulation (EC) No 1907/2006 is amended to include a ban on the use of decaBDE in quantities greater than 0.1% by weight, effective from 2 March 2019. Products placed on the market prior to 2 March 2019 are exempt. Furthermore, the use decaBDE in aircraft is permissible until 2 March 2027.<ref name=\"Commission Regulation (EU) 2017/227\">{{cite journal|last1=The European Commission|title=Commission Regulation (EU) 2017/227|journal=Official Journal of the European Union|date=9 February 2017|volume=L35|pages=6\u20139|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32017R0227&from=EN|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Hexabromocyclododecane]] (''HBCD'' or ''HBCDD'') is a ring consisting of twelve [[carbon]] atoms with six [[bromine]] atoms tied to the ring. The commercially used HBCD is in fact a mixture of different [[isomer]]s. HBCD is toxic to water-living [[organism]]s. The UNEP Stockholm Convention has listed HBCD for elimination, but allowing a temporary exemption for the use in polystyrene insulation foams in buildings.<ref>The final decision is available on the UNEP Stockholm Convention website here: {{cite web |url=http://chm.pops.int/Convention/ConferenceoftheParties(COP)/Decisions/tabid/208/Default.aspx |title=COP Decisions |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925113855/http://chm.pops.int/Convention/ConferenceoftheParties%28COP%29/Decisions/tabid/208/Default.aspx |archivedate=2014-09-25 }}</ref>\n\n[[Tetrabromobisphenol A]] (''TBBPA'' or ''TBBP-A'') is regarded as toxic to water environment.{{Citation needed|date=July 2007}} This flame retardant is mainly used in [[printed circuit board]]s, as a [[wikt:reactive|reactive]]. Since TBBPA is chemically bound to the resin of the printed circuit board, it is less easily released than the loosely applied mixtures in foams such that an EU risk assessment concluded in 2005 that TBBPA poses no risk to human health in that application.<ref>EU Risk Assessment Report (2006) {{cite web |url=http://www.bsef.com/uploads/library/final_tbbpa_human_health_report.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905000058/http://www.bsef.com/uploads/library/final_tbbpa_human_health_report.pdf |archivedate=2014-09-05 }}</ref> TBBPA is also used as an additive in [[acrylonitrile butadiene styrene]] (ABS).\n\n==Contents in plastics==\nContent of brominated flame retardants in different polymers:<ref>Pedro Arias (2001): ''Brominated flame retardants \u2013 an overview''. The Second International Workshop on Brominated Flame Retardants, Stockholm</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polymer\n! Content [%]\n! Substances\n|-\n| [[Polystyrene]] foam\n| 0.8\u20134\n| HBCD\n|-\n| [[High impact polystyrene]]\n| 11\u201315\n| DecaBDE, brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| [[Epoxy resin]]\n| 0-0.1\n| TBBPA\n|-\n| [[Polyamide]]s\n| 13\u201316\n| DecaBDE, brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| [[Polyolefin]]s\n| 5\u20138\n| DecaBDE, propylene dibromo styrene\n|-\n| [[Polyurethane]]s\n| n/a\n| No brominated FR available\n|-\n| [[Polyterephthalate]]\n| 8\u201311\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| Unsaturated [[polyester]]s\n| 13\u201328\n| TBBPA\n|-\n| [[Polycarbonate]]\n| 4\u20136\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| Styrene [[copolymer]]s\n| 12\u201315\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|}\n\n==Production==\n390,000 tons of brominated flame retardants were sold in 2011. This represents 19.7% of the flame retardants market.<ref>Townsend Solutions Estimate, {{cite web |url=http://www.flameretardants-online.com/web/en/106/7ae3d32234954e28e661e506e284da7f.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070150/http://www.flameretardants-online.com/web/en/106/7ae3d32234954e28e661e506e284da7f.htm |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Types of applications==\nThe electronics industry accounts for the greatest consumption of BFRs. In computers, BFRs are used in four main applications: in [[printed circuit board]]s, in components such as [[Electrical connector|connector]]s, in plastic covers, and in [[electrical cable]]s. BFRs are also used in a multitude of products, including, but not exclusively, plastic covers of television sets, carpets, pillows, paints, upholstery, and domestic kitchen appliances.\n\n==Testing for BFR in plastics==\n\nUntil recently testing for BFR has been cumbersome. Cycle time, cost and level of expertise required for the test engineer has precluded the implementation of any screening of plastic components in a manufacturing or in a product qualification/validation environment.\n\nRecently, with the introduction of a new analytical instrument [[IA-Mass]], screening of plastic material alongside a manufacturing line became possible. A five-minute detection cycle and a 20-minute quantification cycle is available to test and to qualify plastic parts as they reach the assembly line. IA-Mass identifies the presence of bromine (PBB, PBDE, and some others), but cannot characterize all the BFRs present in the plastic matrix.\n\nIn February 2009, the [[Institute for Reference Materials and Measurements|Institute for Reference Materials and Measurements (IRMM)]] released two certified reference materials (CRMs) to help analytical laboratories better detect two classes of flame retardants, namely polybrominated diphenyl ethers (PBDEs) and polybrominated biphenyls (PBBs). The two reference materials were custom made to contain all relevant PBDEs and PBBs at levels close to the legal limit set out in the [[RoHS Directive]] of 1 g/kg for the sum of PBBs and PBDEs.\n\n==Environmental and safety issues==\nMany brominated chemicals are under increasing criticism in their use in household furnishings and where children would come into contact with them. Some believe PBDEs could have harmful effects on humans and animals. Increasing concern has prompted some European countries to ban some of them, following the [[precautionary principle]] more common in Europe.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Stiffler | first=Lisa | title=PBDEs: They are everywhere, they accumulate and they spread | newspaper=[[Seattle Post Intelligencer]] | date=March 28, 2007 | url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/309169_pbde28.html}}</ref> Some PBDEs are [[lipophilic]] and bioaccumulative.  PBDEs have been found in people all over the world.<ref>{{cite journal | author1 = Kim Hooper | author2 = Jianwen She | title = Lessons from the Polybrominated Diphenyl Ethers (PBDEs): Precautionary Principle, Primary Prevention, and the Value of Community-Based Body-Burden Monitoring Using Breast Milk | journal = [[Environmental Health Perspectives]] | year = 2003 | volume = 111 | issue = 1 | url = http://www.ehponline.org/members/2003/5438/5438.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081101015833/http://www.ehponline.org/members/2003/5438/5438.html | archivedate = 2008-11-01 | doi = 10.1289/ehp.5438 | pmid = 12515688 | pmc = 1241314 | pages=109\u2013114}}</ref>\n\nSome brominated flame retardants were identified as persistent, bioaccumulative, and toxic to both humans and the environment and were suspected of causing [[Neurobehavioral disorders|neurobehavioral effects]] and [[endocrine disruption]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/oppt/existingchemicals/pubs/actionplans/pbde.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901200633/http://www.epa.gov/oppt/existingchemicals/pubs/actionplans/pbde.html |archivedate=2015-09-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cerc.usgs.gov/pubs/center/pdfdocs/pbde.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508170026/http://www.cerc.usgs.gov/pubs/center/pdfDocs/PBDE.pdf |archivedate=2016-05-08 }}</ref> One particular target group is Firefighters who are exposed to brominated fire retardants during firefighting operations and is resulting in cancer rates that far exceed the general public.<ref>{{cite journal| doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2012.12.070 | pmid=23395527 | volume=91 | issue=10 | title=Persistent organic pollutants including polychlorinated and polybrominated dibenzo-p-dioxins and dibenzofurans in firefighters from Northern California | year=2013 | journal=Chemosphere | pages=1386\u20131394 | last1 = Shaw | first1 = Susan D.| bibcode=2013Chmsp..91.1386S }}</ref> As an example, in Europe, brominated flame retardants have gone through [[Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals|REACH]] and when risks were identified appropriate risk management options were put in place; such was the case for commercial Penta-BDE<ref>European Union Risk Assessment Report of diphenyl ether, pentabromo deriv., 2000  {{cite web|url=http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/781ee1e9-6c90-467e-998b-8910ca2793e5 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026163555/http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/781ee1e9-6c90-467e-998b-8910ca2793e5 |archivedate=2014-10-26 }}</ref> and commercial Octa-BDE.<ref>European Union Risk Assessment Report of diphenyl ether, octabromo deriv., 2003 {{cite web|url=http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/5b10aa46-9a88-4aed-b338-1e06105b924c |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026164133/http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/5b10aa46-9a88-4aed-b338-1e06105b924c |archivedate=2014-10-26 }}</ref>\nGiven the current state of waste disposal in the world, there is a potential for BFRs to be released into the environment.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tris(2,3-dibromopropyl) phosphate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal\n|author1=Kyle D'Silva, Alwyn Fernandes  |author2=Martin Rose\n |lastauthoramp=yes | title = Brominated Organic Micropollutants\u2014Igniting the Flame Retardant Issue\n| journal = Critical Reviews in Environmental Science and Technology\n| year = 2004\n| volume = 34\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 141\u2013207\n| doi = 10.1080/10643380490430672}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Law|first1=Robin J.|last2=Kohler|first2=Martin|last3=Heeb|first3=Norbert V.|last4=Gerecke|first4=Andreas C.|last5=Schmid|first5=Peter|last6=Voorspoels|first6=Stefan|last7=Covaci|first7=Adrian|last8=Becher|first8=Georg|last9=Janak|first9=Karel|title=Hexabromocyclododecane Challenges Scientists and Regulators|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|volume=39|pages=281A|year=2005|doi=10.1021/es053302f|issue=13|bibcode=2005EnST...39..281L}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author= Cynthia A. de Wit\n| title = An overview of brominated flame retardants in the environment\n| journal = [[Chemosphere (journal)|Chemosphere]]\n| year = 2002\n| volume = 46\n| issue = 5\n| pages = 583\u2013624\n| doi = 10.1016/S0045-6535(01)00225-9\n| pmid=11999784| bibcode = 2002Chmsp..46..583D\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author= Young Ran Kim\n| title = Health consequences of exposure to brominated flame retardants: A systematic review\n| journal = [[Chemosphere (journal)|Chemosphere]]\n| year = 2014\n| volume = 106\n| issue = \n| pages = 1\u201319\n| doi = 10.1016/j.chemosphere.2013.12.064\n| pmid=24529398|display-authors=etal| bibcode=2014Chmsp.106....1K}}\n*{{cite journal\n|author1=H. Fromme |author2=G. Becher |author3=B. Hilger |author4=W. V\u00f6lkel | year = 2016\n| title = Brominated flame retardants \u2013 Exposure and risk assessment for the general population\n| journal = [[International Journal of Hygiene and Environmental Health]]\n| volume = 219\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201323\n| doi = 10.1016/j.ijheh.2015.08.004\n| pmid = 26412400\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author1=J. de Boer | author2=H. M. Stapleton\n| year = 2019\n| title = Toward fire safety without chemical risk\n| journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]]\n| volume = 364\n| issue = 6437\n| pages = 231\u2013232\n| doi = 10.1126/science.aax2054\n| pmid = 31000649\n| doi-broken-date=2020-01-22\n| url = https://science.sciencemag.org/content/364/6437/231 | url-access=subscription\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mpi-chemie.com/category/brominated-flame-retardants.html MPI Milebrome - Brominated Flame Retardants]\n* [http://www.bsef.com Bromine Science and Environmental Forum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051227043918/http://www.ebfrip.org/ European Brominated Flame Retardant Industry Panel]\n* SFT: [http://www.sft.no/publikasjoner/2462/ta2462.pdf Current State of Knowledge and Monitoring requirements: Emerging \"new\" Brominated flame retardants in flame retarded products and the environment]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Bromine compounds]]\n[[Category:Organobromides]]\n[[Category:Flame retardants]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brominated flame retardants''' ('''BFRs''') are [[organobromine compound]]s that have an inhibitory effect on combustion chemistry and tend to reduce the flammability of products containing them. The brominated variety of commercialized chemical flame retardants comprise approximately 19.7% of the market. They are effective in plastics and textile applications like electronics, clothes and furniture.\n\n==Types of compounds==\nMany different BFRs are produced [[organic synthesis|synthetically]] with widely varying chemical properties. There are several groups:<ref>Michael J. Dagani, Henry J. Barda, Theodore J. Benya, David C. Sanders \"Bromine Compounds\" Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry 2002, Wiley-VCH, Weinheim.  {{DOI|10.1002/14356007.a04_405}}</ref>\n\n* [[Polybrominated diphenyl ethers]] (PBDEs): [[DecaBDE]], [[OctaBDE]] (not manufactured anymore), [[PentaBDE]] (not manufactured anymore, the first BFR, commercialized in the 1950s)\n* [[Polybrominated biphenyl]] (PBB), not manufactured anymore\n* Brominated cyclohydrocarbons\n* Other brominated flame retardants with different properties and mechanisms\n\n[[Decabromodiphenyl ether]] (''Deca-BDE'' or ''DeBDE'') - In August 2012, the UK authorities proposed decabromodiphenyl ether (Deca-BDE or DeBDE) as a candidate for Authorisation under the EU\u2018s regulatory regime on chemicals, REACH. On 5 July 2013 [[ECHA]] withdrew Deca-BDE from its list of priority substances for Authorisation under REACH, therefore closing the public consultation. On 1 August 2014, ECHA submitted a restriction proposal for Deca-BDE. The agency is proposing a restriction on the manufacture, use and placing on the market of the substance and of mixtures and articles containing it. On 17 September 2014, ECHA submitted the restriction report which initiates a six months public consultation. On 9 February 2017, the [[European Commission]] adopted Regulation EU 2017/227. Article 1 of this regulation states that Regulation (EC) No 1907/2006 is amended to include a ban on the use of decaBDE in quantities greater than 0.1% by weight, effective from 2 March 2019. Products placed on the market prior to 2 March 2019 are exempt. Furthermore, the use decaBDE in aircraft is permissible until 2 March 2027.<ref name=\"Commission Regulation (EU) 2017/227\">{{cite journal|last1=The European Commission|title=Commission Regulation (EU) 2017/227|journal=Official Journal of the European Union|date=9 February 2017|volume=L35|pages=6\u20139|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32017R0227&from=EN|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Hexabromocyclododecane]] (''HBCD'' or ''HBCDD'') is a ring consisting of twelve [[carbon]] atoms with six [[bromine]] atoms tied to the ring. The commercially used HBCD is in fact a mixture of different [[isomer]]s. HBCD is toxic to water-living [[organism]]s. The UNEP Stockholm Convention has listed HBCD for elimination, but allowing a temporary exemption for the use in polystyrene insulation foams in buildings.<ref>The final decision is available on the UNEP Stockholm Convention website here: {{cite web |url=http://chm.pops.int/Convention/ConferenceoftheParties(COP)/Decisions/tabid/208/Default.aspx |title=COP Decisions |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925113855/http://chm.pops.int/Convention/ConferenceoftheParties%28COP%29/Decisions/tabid/208/Default.aspx |archivedate=2014-09-25 }}</ref>\n\n[[Tetrabromobisphenol A]] (''TBBPA'' or ''TBBP-A'') is regarded as toxic to water environment.{{Citation needed|date=July 2007}} This flame retardant is mainly used in [[printed circuit board]]s, as a [[wikt:reactive|reactive]]. Since TBBPA is chemically bound to the resin of the printed circuit board, it is less easily released than the loosely applied mixtures in foams such that an EU risk assessment concluded in 2005 that TBBPA poses no risk to human health in that application.<ref>EU Risk Assessment Report (2006) {{cite web |url=http://www.bsef.com/uploads/library/final_tbbpa_human_health_report.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905000058/http://www.bsef.com/uploads/library/final_tbbpa_human_health_report.pdf |archivedate=2014-09-05 }}</ref> TBBPA is also used as an additive in [[acrylonitrile butadiene styrene]] (ABS).\n\n==Contents in plastics==\nContent of brominated flame retardants in different polymers:<ref>Pedro Arias (2001): ''Brominated flame retardants \u2013 an overview''. The Second International Workshop on Brominated Flame Retardants, Stockholm</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Polymer\n! Content [%]\n! Substances\n|-\n| [[Polystyrene]] foam\n| 0.8\u20134\n| HBCD\n|-\n| [[High impact polystyrene]]\n| 11\u201315\n| DecaBDE, brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| [[Epoxy resin]]\n| 0-0.1\n| TBBPA\n|-\n| [[Polyamide]]s\n| 13\u201316\n| DecaBDE, brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| [[Polyolefin]]s\n| 5\u20138\n| DecaBDE, propylene dibromo styrene\n|-\n| [[Polyurethane]]s\n| n/a\n| No brominated FR available\n|-\n| [[Polyterephthalate]]\n| 8\u201311\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| Unsaturated [[polyester]]s\n| 13\u201328\n| TBBPA\n|-\n| [[Polycarbonate]]\n| 4\u20136\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|-\n| Styrene [[copolymer]]s\n| 12\u201315\n| Brominated polystyrene\n|}\n\n==Production==\n390,000 tons of brominated flame retardants were sold in 2011. This represents 19.7% of the flame retardants market.<ref>Townsend Solutions Estimate, {{cite web |url=http://www.flameretardants-online.com/web/en/106/7ae3d32234954e28e661e506e284da7f.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070150/http://www.flameretardants-online.com/web/en/106/7ae3d32234954e28e661e506e284da7f.htm |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n==Types of applications==\nThe electronics industry accounts for the greatest consumption of BFRs. In computers, BFRs are used in four main applications: in [[printed circuit board]]s, in components such as [[Electrical connector|connector]]s, in plastic covers, and in [[electrical cable]]s. BFRs are also used in a multitude of products, including, but not exclusively, plastic covers of television sets, carpets, pillows, paints, upholstery, and domestic kitchen appliances.\n\n==Testing for BFR in plastics==\n\nUntil recently testing for BFR has been cumbersome. Cycle time, cost and level of expertise required for the test engineer has precluded the implementation of any screening of plastic components in a manufacturing or in a product qualification/validation environment.\n\nRecently, with the introduction of a new analytical instrument [[IA-Mass]], screening of plastic material alongside a manufacturing line became possible. A five-minute detection cycle and a 20-minute quantification cycle is available to test and to qualify plastic parts as they reach the assembly line. IA-Mass identifies the presence of bromine (PBB, PBDE, and some others), but cannot characterize all the BFRs present in the plastic matrix.\n\nIn February 2009, the [[Institute for Reference Materials and Measurements|Institute for Reference Materials and Measurements (IRMM)]] released two certified reference materials (CRMs) to help analytical laboratories better detect two classes of flame retardants, namely polybrominated diphenyl ethers (PBDEs) and polybrominated biphenyls (PBBs). The two reference materials were custom made to contain all relevant PBDEs and PBBs at levels close to the legal limit set out in the [[RoHS Directive]] of 1 g/kg for the sum of PBBs and PBDEs.\n\n==Environmental and safety issues==\nMany brominated chemicals are under increasing criticism in their use in household furnishings and where children would come into contact with them. Some believe PBDEs could have harmful effects on humans and animals. Increasing concern has prompted some European countries to ban some of them, following the [[precautionary principle]] more common in Europe.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Stiffler | first=Lisa | title=PBDEs: They are everywhere, they accumulate and they spread | newspaper=[[Seattle Post Intelligencer]] | date=March 28, 2007 | url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/309169_pbde28.html}}</ref> Some PBDEs are [[lipophilic]] and bioaccumulative.  PBDEs have been found in people all over the world.<ref>{{cite journal | author1 = Kim Hooper | author2 = Jianwen She | title = Lessons from the Polybrominated Diphenyl Ethers (PBDEs): Precautionary Principle, Primary Prevention, and the Value of Community-Based Body-Burden Monitoring Using Breast Milk | journal = [[Environmental Health Perspectives]] | year = 2003 | volume = 111 | issue = 1 | url = http://www.ehponline.org/members/2003/5438/5438.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081101015833/http://www.ehponline.org/members/2003/5438/5438.html | archivedate = 2008-11-01 | doi = 10.1289/ehp.5438 | pmid = 12515688 | pmc = 1241314 | pages=109\u2013114}}</ref>\n\nSome brominated flame retardants were identified as persistent, bioaccumulative, and toxic to both humans and the environment and were suspected of causing [[Neurobehavioral disorders|neurobehavioral effects]] and [[endocrine disruption]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/oppt/existingchemicals/pubs/actionplans/pbde.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901200633/http://www.epa.gov/oppt/existingchemicals/pubs/actionplans/pbde.html |archivedate=2015-09-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cerc.usgs.gov/pubs/center/pdfdocs/pbde.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508170026/http://www.cerc.usgs.gov/pubs/center/pdfDocs/PBDE.pdf |archivedate=2016-05-08 }}</ref> One particular target group is Firefighters who are exposed to brominated fire retardants during firefighting operations and is resulting in cancer rates that far exceed the general public.<ref>{{cite journal| doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2012.12.070 | pmid=23395527 | volume=91 | issue=10 | title=Persistent organic pollutants including polychlorinated and polybrominated dibenzo-p-dioxins and dibenzofurans in firefighters from Northern California | year=2013 | journal=Chemosphere | pages=1386\u20131394 | last1 = Shaw | first1 = Susan D.| bibcode=2013Chmsp..91.1386S }}</ref> As an example, in Europe, brominated flame retardants have gone through [[Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals|REACH]] and when risks were identified appropriate risk management options were put in place; such was the case for commercial Penta-BDE<ref>European Union Risk Assessment Report of diphenyl ether, pentabromo deriv., 2000  {{cite web|url=http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/781ee1e9-6c90-467e-998b-8910ca2793e5 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026163555/http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/781ee1e9-6c90-467e-998b-8910ca2793e5 |archivedate=2014-10-26 }}</ref> and commercial Octa-BDE.<ref>European Union Risk Assessment Report of diphenyl ether, octabromo deriv., 2003 {{cite web|url=http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/5b10aa46-9a88-4aed-b338-1e06105b924c |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026164133/http://echa.europa.eu/documents/10162/5b10aa46-9a88-4aed-b338-1e06105b924c |archivedate=2014-10-26 }}</ref>\nGiven the current state of waste disposal in the world, there is a potential for BFRs to be released into the environment.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tris(2,3-dibromopropyl) phosphate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal\n|author1=Kyle D'Silva, Alwyn Fernandes  |author2=Martin Rose\n |lastauthoramp=yes | title = Brominated Organic Micropollutants\u2014Igniting the Flame Retardant Issue\n| journal = Critical Reviews in Environmental Science and Technology\n| year = 2004\n| volume = 34\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 141\u2013207\n| doi = 10.1080/10643380490430672}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Law|first1=Robin J.|last2=Kohler|first2=Martin|last3=Heeb|first3=Norbert V.|last4=Gerecke|first4=Andreas C.|last5=Schmid|first5=Peter|last6=Voorspoels|first6=Stefan|last7=Covaci|first7=Adrian|last8=Becher|first8=Georg|last9=Janak|first9=Karel|title=Hexabromocyclododecane Challenges Scientists and Regulators|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|volume=39|pages=281A|year=2005|doi=10.1021/es053302f|issue=13|bibcode=2005EnST...39..281L}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author= Cynthia A. de Wit\n| title = An overview of brominated flame retardants in the environment\n| journal = [[Chemosphere (journal)|Chemosphere]]\n| year = 2002\n| volume = 46\n| issue = 5\n| pages = 583\u2013624\n| doi = 10.1016/S0045-6535(01)00225-9\n| pmid=11999784| bibcode = 2002Chmsp..46..583D\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author= Young Ran Kim\n| title = Health consequences of exposure to brominated flame retardants: A systematic review\n| journal = [[Chemosphere (journal)|Chemosphere]]\n| year = 2014\n| volume = 106\n| issue = \n| pages = 1\u201319\n| doi = 10.1016/j.chemosphere.2013.12.064\n| pmid=24529398|display-authors=etal| bibcode=2014Chmsp.106....1K}}\n*{{cite journal\n|author1=H. Fromme |author2=G. Becher |author3=B. Hilger |author4=W. V\u00f6lkel | year = 2016\n| title = Brominated flame retardants \u2013 Exposure and risk assessment for the general population\n| journal = [[International Journal of Hygiene and Environmental Health]]\n| volume = 219\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201323\n| doi = 10.1016/j.ijheh.2015.08.004\n| pmid = 26412400\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n| author1=J. de Boer | author2=H. M. Stapleton\n| year = 2019\n| title = Toward fire safety without chemical risk\n| journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]]\n| volume = 364\n| issue = 6437\n| pages = 231\u2013232\n| doi = 10.1126/science.aax2054\n| pmid = 31000649\n| doi-broken-date=2020-01-22\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mpi-chemie.com/category/brominated-flame-retardants.html MPI Milebrome - Brominated Flame Retardants]\n* [http://www.bsef.com Bromine Science and Environmental Forum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051227043918/http://www.ebfrip.org/ European Brominated Flame Retardant Industry Panel]\n* SFT: [http://www.sft.no/publikasjoner/2462/ta2462.pdf Current State of Knowledge and Monitoring requirements: Emerging \"new\" Brominated flame retardants in flame retarded products and the environment]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Bromine compounds]]\n[[Category:Organobromides]]\n[[Category:Flame retardants]]\n", "name_user": "Hqb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:doi still broken, but add working url", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brominated_flame_retardant"}
{"title_page": "Gloria de Souza", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gloria de Souza\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = 5 April 1937\n| death_date         = 3 April 2013\n| occupation         = Educator, Social Entrepreneur, Reformer, Founder\n| organization       = Parisar Asha\n| website            = parisarasha.com\n}}\n'''Gloria de Souza''' (5 April 1937 \u2013 3 April 2013)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Gloria-de-Souza/articleshow/46785680.cms|title=Gloria de Souza - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> was a social entrepreneur and first fellow the international non-profit organization [[Ashoka (non-profit organization)|Ashoka]]. She was known for her work in educational reform and modern [[social entrepreneurship]]. She began working in Mumbai, India as a primary school teacher and in 1971, while she was teaching at a private Jesuit school, de Souza was prompted to make changes by adopting experiential and environmental methods in her curriculum.<ref name=\":0\">Bornstein, David. \"From Little Acorns Do Great Trees Grow, in ''How to Change the World: Social Entrepreneurs and the Power of New Ideas''. George Mason University. Retrieved 15 March 2020. \u00a0</ref> She noted that India's rate of [[Brain-drain|brain drain]] was high at the time and wanted to change the educational system as a whole.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Social Entrepreneurship ==\n\n==== Ashoka and Parisar Asha ====\nDe Souza became a fellow of the then newly founded Ashoka: Innovators for the Public in 1982 by [[Bill Drayton]] and his colleagues elected de Souza for her talent and commitment to the cause, as well as business acumen. With support from Ashoka, she quit her teaching job and proceeded to build her own local NGO that same year, [[Parisar Asha]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Worth|first=Michael J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lsFqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA438&dq=%22Gloria+de+Souza%22+pioneer&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwja4Y2e5szoAhWrlnIEHRRTBasQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Gloria%20de%20Souza%22%20pioneer&f=false|title=Nonprofit Management: Principles and Practice|date=24 August 2018|publisher=SAGE Publications|year=|isbn=978-1-5063-9687-3|location=|pages=438|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThrough Parisar Asha, de Souza developed the Environmental Studies program. She successfully persuaded the Mumbai municipal school board into allowing 1,700 public schools to conduct a test pilot for environmental studies. In the late 1980s the Indian government adopted it into its public education system, making it a curriculum requirement for students grade 1\u20133.<ref name=\":2\">Frank, Peter M. and Gordon Shockley. \"The functions of government in social entrepreneurship: theory and preliminary evidence.\" ''Regional Science Policy & Practice'' 3, no. 3 (June 2011): 181-198.</ref> Entitled Environmental Studies Approach and Learning (ESAL), the program is now the core principle in Parisar Asha.\n\n==== Other institutions ====\nDe Souza collaborated with many other NGOs, government agencies and corporations on educational reform. Her 1988 collaboration with [[Defence for Children International]] evaluated street children and public institutions. They identified possible institutions for 'reception,' 'observation,' and 'rehabilitation,' and found on-the-ground that bureaucratic incompetencies hindered the education and protection of these children worldwide.<ref name=\":3\">Williams, Christopher. \"'STREET CHILDREN' AND EDUCATION: a comparative study of European and third world approaches.\" PhD diss., University of Birmingham, 1990.</ref>\n\nIn 2001, educational centers in Indian mega-cities received a commission from the United Nations Educational, Scientific And Cultural Organization in New Delhi to conduct a study on street and working children in India. In the published report, she reported results on rehabilitation of working children.<ref name=\":4\">India National Commission for co-operation with UNESCO. [https://unesdoc.unesco.org/ark:/48223/pf0000126355/PDF/126355engo.pdf.multi \"Education for Street and Working Children in India.\"] New Delhi (2001): United Nations Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization''.'' Retrieved 15 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== Personal life and philosophy ==\nDe Souza was born on 5 April 1937.<ref name=\":1\" /> She has stated that her goal was never success, but rather, fruitfulness. She attributed her vision, tenacity, and openminded-ness towards introducing tenets of modern, Western education to developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.changemakers.com/blog/gloria-de-souza-on-how-to-grow-into-a-fruitful|title=Gloria de Souza on how to grow into a &quot;fruitful&quot; entrepreneur|website=Changemakers|language=en-us|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">Richez-Battesti N., Petrella F. (2013) \"Social Entrepreneurship,\" in ''Encyclopedia of Creativity, Invention, Innovation and Entrepreneurship,'' edited by Carayannis E.G. Springer (2013): New York, NY.</ref>\n\nShe died on 3 April 2013.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian women educators]]\n[[Category:Social entrepreneurs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gloria de Souza\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = 5 April 1937\n| death_date         = 3 April 2013\n| occupation         = Educator, Social Entrepreneur, Reformer, Founder\n| organization       = Parisar Asha\n| website            = parisarasha.com\n}}\n'''Gloria de Souza''' (5 April 1937 \u2013 3 April 2013)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Gloria-de-Souza/articleshow/46785680.cms|title=Gloria de Souza - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> was a social entrepreneur and first fellow the international non-profit organization [[Ashoka (non-profit organization)|Ashoka]]. She was known for her work in educational reform and modern [[social entrepreneurship]]. She began working in Mumbai, India as a primary school teacher and in 1971, while she was teaching at a private Jesuit school, de Souza was prompted to make changes by adopting experiential and environmental methods in her curriculum.<ref name=\":0\">Bornstein, David. \"From Little Acorns Do Great Trees Grow, in ''How to Change the World: Social Entrepreneurs and the Power of New Ideas''. George Mason University. Retrieved 15 March 2020. \u00a0</ref> She noted that India's rate of [[Brain-drain|brain drain]] was high at the time and wanted to change the educational system as a whole.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Social Entrepreneurship ==\n\n==== Ashoka and Parisar Asha ====\nDe Souza became a fellow of the then newly founded Ashoka: Innovators for the Public in 1982 by [[Bill Drayton]] and his colleagues elected de Souza for her talent and commitment to the cause, as well as business acumen. With support from Ashoka, she quit her teaching job and proceeded to build her own local NGO that same year, [[Parisar Asha]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Worth|first=Michael J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lsFqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA438&dq=%22Gloria+de+Souza%22+pioneer&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwja4Y2e5szoAhWrlnIEHRRTBasQ6AEwAHoECAMQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Gloria%20de%20Souza%22%20pioneer&f=false|title=Nonprofit Management: Principles and Practice|date=24 August 2018|publisher=SAGE Publications|year=|isbn=978-1-5063-9687-3|location=|pages=438|language=en}}</ref> \n\nThrough Parisar Asha, de Souza developed the Environmental Studies program. She successfully persuaded the Mumbai municipal school board into allowing 1,700 public schools to conduct a test pilot for environmental studies. In the late 1980s the Indian government adopted it into its public education system, making it a curriculum requirement for students grade 1-3.<ref name=\":2\">Frank, Peter M. and Gordon Shockley. \"The functions of government in social entrepreneurship: theory and preliminary evidence.\" ''Regional Science Policy & Practice'' 3, no. 3 (June 2011): 181-198.</ref> Entitled Environmental Studies Approach and Learning (ESAL), the program is now the core principle in Parisar Asha.\n\n==== Other institutions ====\nDe Souza collaborated with many other NGOs, government agencies and corporations on educational reform. Her 1988 collaboration with [[Defence for Children International]] evaluated street children and public institutions. They identified possible institutions for 'reception,' 'observation,' and 'rehabilitation,' and found on-the-ground that bureaucratic incompetencies hindered the education and protection of these children worldwide.<ref name=\":3\">Williams, Christopher. \"'STREET CHILDREN' AND EDUCATION: a comparative study of European and third world approaches.\" PhD diss., University of Birmingham, 1990.</ref> \n\nIn 2001, educational centers in Indian mega-cities received a commission from the United Nations Educational, Scientific And Cultural Organization in New Delhi to conduct a study on street and working children in India. In the published report, she reported results on rehabilitation of working children.<ref name=\":4\">India National Commission for co-operation with UNESCO. [https://unesdoc.unesco.org/ark:/48223/pf0000126355/PDF/126355engo.pdf.multi \"Education for Street and Working Children in India.\"] New Delhi (2001): United Nations Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization''.'' Retrieved 15 March 2020.</ref>  \n\n== Personal life and philosophy ==\nDe Souza was born on 5 April 1937.<ref name=\":1\" /> She has stated that her goal was never success, but rather, fruitfulness. She attributed her vision, tenacity, and openminded-ness towards introducing tenets of modern, Western education to developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.changemakers.com/blog/gloria-de-souza-on-how-to-grow-into-a-fruitful|title=Gloria de Souza on how to grow into a &quot;fruitful&quot; entrepreneur|website=Changemakers|language=en-us|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">Richez-Battesti N., Petrella F. (2013) \"Social Entrepreneurship,\" in ''Encyclopedia of Creativity, Invention, Innovation and Entrepreneurship,'' edited by Carayannis E.G. Springer (2013): New York, NY.</ref>\n\nShe died on 3 April 2013.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian women educators]]\n[[Category:Social entrepreneurs]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1-3 \u2192 1\u20133", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gloria_de_Souza"}
{"title_page": "Tribe of Naphtali", "text_new": "{{Tribes of Israel}}\nThe '''Tribe of Naphtali''' ({{Hebrew Name|\u05e0\u05b7\u05e4\u05b0\u05ea\u05b8\u05bc\u05dc\u05b4\u05d9|Naftali|Nap\u0304t\u0101l\u00ee|\"My struggle\"}}) was one of the northernmost of the [[twelve tribes of Israel]]. It is one of the [[ten lost tribes]].\n\n== Biblical narratives==\nIn the biblical account, following the completion of the conquest of [[Canaan]] by the [[Israelite]]s, [[Joshua]] allocated the land among the twelve tribes. [[Kenneth Kitchen]], a well-known conservative biblical scholar, dates this event to slightly after 1200 BCE.<ref name = \"pnxthp\">Kitchen, Kenneth A. (2003), ''On the Reliability of the Old Testament'' (Grand Rapids, Michigan. William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company)({{ISBN|0-8028-4960-1}})</ref> However, the consensus view of modern, Critical Biblical scholars is that the conquest of Joshua as described in the Book of Joshua never occurred.<ref name=\"BakerArnold2004\">\u201cBesides the rejection of the Albrightian \u2018conquest' model, the general consensus among OT scholars is that the Book of Joshua has no value in the historical reconstruction. They see the book as an ideological retrojection from a later period \u2014 either as early as the reign of Josiah or as late as the Hasmonean period.\u201d\n {{cite book|editor1=David W. Baker|editor2=Bill T. Arnold|author=K. Lawson Younger Jr.|chapter=Early Israel in Recent Biblical Scholarship|title=The Face of Old Testament Studies: A Survey of Contemporary Approaches|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vO8XRZyhvpMC&pg=PA200|date=1 October 2004|publisher=Baker Academic|isbn=978-0-8010-2871-7|page=200}}</ref><ref name=\"Congress1999\">\u201dIt behooves us to ask, in spite of the fact that the overwhelming consensus of modern scholarship is that Joshua is a pious fiction composed by the deuteronomistic school, how does and how has the Jewish community dealt with these foundational narratives, saturated as they are with acts of violence against others?\" {{cite book|author=Carl S. Ehrlich|title=Jewish Studies at the Turn of the Twentieth Century, Volume 1: Biblical, Rabbinical, and Medieval Studies|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ZlRPQJ8Qd4C&pg=PA117|year=1999|chapter=Joshua, Judaism and Genocide|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11554-5|page=117}}</ref><ref name=\"BerlinBrettler2014\">\u201dRecent decades, for example, have seen a remarkable reevaluation of evidence concerning the conquest of the land of Canaan by Joshua. As more sites have been excavated, there has been a growing consensus that the main story of Joshua, that of a speedy and complete conquest (e.g. Josh. 11.23: 'Thus Joshua conquered the whole country, just as the {{Lord}} had promised Moses') is contradicted by the archaeological record, though there are indications of ''some'' destruction and conquest at the appropriate time.{{cite book|author1=Adele Berlin|author2=Marc Zvi Brettler|title=The Jewish Study Bible: Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yErYBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT951|date=17 October 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-939387-9|page=951}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Bible Joshua assigned Naphtali the eastern side of [[the Galilee]] (on the immediate west of the [[Sea of Galilee]]), in the areas now known as the [[Lower Galilee]], and [[Upper Galilee]], bordered on the west by [[Tribe of Asher|Asher]], in the north by [[Tribe of Dan|Dan]], in the south by [[Tribe of Zebulun|Zebulun]], and by the [[Jordan River]] on the east.<ref>{{bibleverse||Joshua|19:32-39|HE}}</ref> The most significant city was [[Tel Hazor|Hazor]].\n\nIn this region, bordering the Sea of Galilee, was the highly fertile plain of [[Gennesaret]], characterised by [[Josephus]] as the ''ambition of nature, an earthly paradise'',<ref>{{JewishEncyclopedia|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=N&artid=57|article=Naphtali, Tribe of}}</ref> and with the southern portion of the region acting as a natural [[mountain pass|pass]] between the highlands of [[Canaan]], several major roads (such as those from [[Damascus]] to [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] and [[Acre, Israel|Acre]]) ran through it.<ref>G. A. Smith, \"The Historical Geography of the Holy Land,\"</ref> The prosperity this situation brought is seemingly [[prophecy|prophesied]] in the [[Blessing of Moses]], though [[textual criticism|textual scholars]] view this as a [[postdiction]], dating the poem to well after the tribe had been established in the land.<ref>[[Richard Elliott Friedman]], ''[[Richard Elliott Friedman#Writings|Who Wrote the Bible?]]'' (Harper San Francisco) (1987) {{ISBN|0-06-063035-3}}</ref><ref>''[[Peake's commentary on the Bible]]''</ref>\n\nFrom after the conquest of the land by Joshua until the formation of the first [[Kingdom of Israel (united kingdom)|Kingdom of Israel]] in c. 1050 BC, the Tribe of Naphtali was a part of a loose confederation of Israelite tribes. No central government existed, and in times of crisis the people were led by ad hoc leaders known as [[Biblical judges|Judges]] (see the [[Book of Judges]]). With the growth of the threat from Philistine incursions, the Israelite tribes decided to form a strong centralised monarchy to meet the challenge, and the Tribe of Naphtali joined the new kingdom with [[Saul]] as the first king. After the death of Saul, all the tribes other than Judah remained loyal to the House of Saul, but after the death of [[Ish-bosheth]], Saul's son and successor to the throne of Israel, the Tribe of Naphtali joined the other northern Israelite tribes in making [[David]], who was then the king of Judah, king of a re-united Kingdom of Israel. However, on the accession of [[Rehoboam]], David's grandson, in c. 930 BC the northern tribes split from the [[Davidic line|House of David]] to reform a Kingdom of Israel as the Northern Kingdom.\n\nIn c. 732 BCE, [[Pekah]] allied with [[Rezin]], king of [[Aram (biblical region)|Aram]], threatened [[Jerusalem]], and [[Ahaz]], [[king of Judah]], appealed to [[Tiglath-Pileser III]], the king of [[Assyria]], for help. After Ahaz paid tribute to Tiglath-Pileser, ({{bibleverse|2|Kings|16:7-9|NIV}}) Tiglath-Pileser sacked Damascus and Israel, annexing Aram<ref name=Grabbe>Lester L. Grabbe, ''Ancient Israel: What Do We Know and How Do We Know It?'' (New York: T&T Clark, 2007): 134</ref> and a large part of Israel, \"including all the land of Naphtali.\" According to {{bibleverse|2|Kings|16:9|NIV}} and {{bibleverse-nb|2|Kings|15:29|NIV}}, the population of Aram and the annexed part of Israel was deported to Assyria. The kingdom of Israel continued to exist until c. 723 BC, when it was again invaded by [[Assyria]] and the rest of the population deported.\n\nFrom that time, the Tribe of Naphtali has been counted as one of the [[Ten Lost Tribes]] of Israel. Psalms 1:24\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:12 Tribes of Israel Map.svg|thumb|right|250px|Map of the 12 tribes of Israel. Naphtali is located in the north.]]\n\nAccording to the [[Torah]], the tribe consisted of descendants of [[Naphtali]], a son of [[Jacob]] and [[Bilhah]], from whom it took its name. However, Arthur Peake views this as a [[postdiction]], an [[eponym]]ous [[metaphor]] providing an [[aetiology]] of the connectedness of the tribe to others in the Israelite confederation.<ref name=\"Peake's commentary on the Bible\">''Peake's Commentary on the Bible''</ref>\n\n==Character==\n[[Militarism]] is featured in Naphtali's history. In the ancient [[Song of Deborah]], Naphtali is commended, along with Zebulun, for risking their lives in the fight against [[Sisera]];<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|5:18|HE}}</ref> in the prose account of the event,<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|4|HE}}</ref> which Arthur Peake regards as a much later narrative based on the poem,<ref name=\"Peake's commentary on the Bible\"/><ref>''Jewish Encyclopedia'', ''Song of Deborah'</ref> there is the addition that [[Barak]], the leader of the anti-Sisera forces, hails from the tribe of Naphtali.<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|4:6|HE}}</ref> In the [[Gideon]] narrative Naphtali are one of the tribes which join in an attack against [[Midian]]ite invaders, though Arthur Peake regards the Gideon narrative as being spliced together from at least three earlier texts, the oldest of which describes only personal vengeance by Gideon and 300 men of his own clan, not a battle in which the rest of the northern tribes join him.<ref>''Jewish Encyclopedia'', ''Gideon''</ref> In the [[Blessing of Jacob]], which textual scholars date to 700-600 BC - and thus a postdiction, Naphtali is compared to a ''[[deer|hind]] let loose'', and commended for giving ''goodly words''.<ref>{{bibleverse||Genesis|49:21}}</ref>\n\nThe territory allotted to the tribe in [[Canaan]] was in the extreme north, and was bordered on the north by the [[Litani River]], on the east by the [[River Jordan]] until it was {{convert|12|mi|km}} south of the [[Sea of Galilee]], on the west by the tribes of [[Asher]] and [[Zebulun|Zabulon]]; and on the south by the tribe of [[Issachar]].<ref>{{bibleverse||Joshua|19:33-34|HE}} quoted in {{CathEncy|wstitle=Nephtali}}</ref>\nThe symbol of the tribe is a gazelle-a very quick animal. The people of Naftali is traditionally thought of as swift (swift runners).{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}\n\n==Fate==\nAs part of the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]], during one of the several wars between the Asa of the [[Kingdom of Judah|kingdoms of Judah]] and Baasha of Israel, the tribe of Naphtali was persecuted by [[Ben-Hadad I|Ben-Hadad]], the king of [[Aram-Damascus]], on behalf of [[Asa of Judah|Asa]], the king of Judah, and desolated. Again, in the reign of Pekah this tribe was among the first to feel the iron hand of Assyria and to suffer the deportation of many captives ({{bibleverse|1 Kings|15:20|KJV}}; {{bibleverse|2 Kings|15:20|KJV}}). In a reference to this incident ([[Isaiah 9:1]]\u2013[[Isaiah 9:2|2]]) the prophet Isaiah anticipates that the same region will see the dawn of the Messianic deliverance. Naphtali, one of the most northerly tribes, became one of the first to be conquered. With the land taken, [[Assyrian Exile|the tribe was exiled]]; the manner of their exile led to [[Lost Ten Tribes|their further history being lost]]. One of the famous battles of the Maccabean war was fought near Kedesh-naphtali about B.C. 150, when Jonathan defeated Demetrius, King of Syria ({{bibleverse|1 Maccabees|11:63-73|KJV}}; Josephus, \"Ant.\" xiii. 5, \u00a7 6).{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Descendants==\n\nThere has been speculation that the [[Bukharian Jews]] of Central Asia are the descendants of the Naphtali tribe.<ref>Ehrlich, M. Avrum ''Encyclopedia of the Jewish Diaspora: Origins, Experiences, and Culture'' ABL-CIO October 2008 {{ISBN|978-1-85109-873-6}} p.84 [https://books.google.com/books?id=PF9_EG3VaaUC&pg=PT110&lpg=PT110&dq=Bukharan+lost+tribe+of+naphtali&source=bl&ots=9ufoDz3BBM&sig=eqykSSXjtenxuF5dXlV_TF2kePI&hl=en&ei=LiD2SrD6HpaB8QbUo4jzCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CBsQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=&f=false]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External link==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Eastons}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish Lebanese history|Naphtali]]\n[[Category:Jewish Syrian history|Naphtali]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Israel|Naphtali]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tribes of Israel}}\nThe '''Tribe of Naphtali''' ({{Hebrew Name|\u05e0\u05b7\u05e4\u05b0\u05ea\u05b8\u05bc\u05dc\u05b4\u05d9|Naftali|Nap\u0304t\u0101l\u00ee|\"My struggle\"}}) was one of the northernmost of the [[twelve tribes of Israel]]. It is one of the [[ten lost tribes]].\n\n== Biblical narratives==\nIn the biblical account, following the completion of the conquest of [[Canaan]] by the [[Israelite]]s, [[Joshua]] allocated the land among the twelve tribes. [[Kenneth Kitchen]], a well-known conservative biblical scholar, dates this event to slightly after 1200 BCE.<ref name = \"pnxthp\">Kitchen, Kenneth A. (2003), ''On the Reliability of the Old Testament'' (Grand Rapids, Michigan. William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company)({{ISBN|0-8028-4960-1}})</ref> However, the consensus view of modern, Critical Biblical scholars is that the conquest of Joshua as described in the Book of Joshua never occurred.<ref name=\"BakerArnold2004\">\u201cBesides the rejection of the Albrightian \u2018conquest' model, the general consensus among OT scholars is that the Book of Joshua has no value in the historical reconstruction. They see the book as an ideological retrojection from a later period \u2014 either as early as the reign of Josiah or as late as the Hasmonean period.\u201d\n {{cite book|editor1=David W. Baker|editor2=Bill T. Arnold|author=K. Lawson Younger Jr.|chapter=Early Israel in Recent Biblical Scholarship|title=The Face of Old Testament Studies: A Survey of Contemporary Approaches|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vO8XRZyhvpMC&pg=PA200|date=1 October 2004|publisher=Baker Academic|isbn=978-0-8010-2871-7|page=200}}</ref><ref name=\"Congress1999\">\u201dIt behooves us to ask, in spite of the fact that the overwhelming consensus of modern scholarship is that Joshua is a pious fiction composed by the deuteronomistic school, how does and how has the Jewish community dealt with these foundational narratives, saturated as they are with acts of violence against others?\" {{cite book|author=Carl S. Ehrlich|title=Jewish Studies at the Turn of the Twentieth Century, Volume 1: Biblical, Rabbinical, and Medieval Studies|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ZlRPQJ8Qd4C&pg=PA117|year=1999|chapter=Joshua, Judaism and Genocide|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-11554-5|page=117}}</ref><ref name=\"BerlinBrettler2014\">\u201dRecent decades, for example, have seen a remarkable reevaluation of evidence concerning the conquest of the land of Canaan by Joshua. As more sites have been excavated, there has been a growing consensus that the main story of Joshua, that of a speedy and complete conquest (e.g. Josh. 11.23: 'Thus Joshua conquered the whole country, just as the {{Lord}} had promised Moses') is contradicted by the archaeological record, though there are indications of ''some'' destruction and conquest at the appropriate time.{{cite book|author1=Adele Berlin|author2=Marc Zvi Brettler|title=The Jewish Study Bible: Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yErYBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT951|date=17 October 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-939387-9|page=951}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Bible Joshua assigned Naphtali the eastern side of [[the Galilee]] (on the immediate west of the [[Sea of Galilee]]), in the areas now known as the [[Lower Galilee]], and [[Upper Galilee]], bordered on the west by [[Tribe of Asher|Asher]], in the north by [[Tribe of Dan|Dan]], in the south by [[Tribe of Zebulun|Zebulun]], and by the [[Jordan River]] on the east.<ref>{{bibleverse||Joshua|19:32-39|HE}}</ref> The most significant city was [[Tel Hazor|Hazor]].\n\nIn this region, bordering the Sea of Galilee, was the highly fertile plain of [[Gennesaret]], characterised by [[Josephus]] as the ''ambition of nature, an earthly paradise'',<ref>{{JewishEncyclopedia|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?letter=N&artid=57|article=Naphtali, Tribe of}}</ref> and with the southern portion of the region acting as a natural [[mountain pass|pass]] between the highlands of [[Canaan]], several major roads (such as those from [[Damascus]] to [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] and [[Acre, Israel|Acre]]) ran through it.<ref>G. A. Smith, \"The Historical Geography of the Holy Land,\"</ref> The prosperity this situation brought is seemingly [[prophecy|prophesied]] in the [[Blessing of Moses]], though [[textual criticism|textual scholars]] view this as a [[postdiction]], dating the poem to well after the tribe had been established in the land.<ref>[[Richard Elliott Friedman]], ''[[Richard Elliott Friedman#Writings|Who Wrote the Bible?]]'' (Harper San Francisco) (1987) {{ISBN|0-06-063035-3}}</ref><ref>''[[Peake's commentary on the Bible]]''</ref>\n\nFrom after the conquest of the land by Joshua until the formation of the first [[Kingdom of Israel (united kingdom)|Kingdom of Israel]] in c. 1050 BC, the Tribe of Naphtali was a part of a loose confederation of Israelite tribes. No central government existed, and in times of crisis the people were led by ad hoc leaders known as [[Biblical judges|Judges]] (see the [[Book of Judges]]). With the growth of the threat from Philistine incursions, the Israelite tribes decided to form a strong centralised monarchy to meet the challenge, and the Tribe of Naphtali joined the new kingdom with [[Saul]] as the first king. After the death of Saul, all the tribes other than Judah remained loyal to the House of Saul, but after the death of [[Ish-bosheth]], Saul's son and successor to the throne of Israel, the Tribe of Naphtali joined the other northern Israelite tribes in making [[David]], who was then the king of Judah, king of a re-united Kingdom of Israel. However, on the accession of [[Rehoboam]], David's grandson, in c. 930 BC the northern tribes split from the [[Davidic line|House of David]] to reform a Kingdom of Israel as the Northern Kingdom.\n\nIn c. 732 BCE, [[Pekah]] allied with [[Rezin]], king of [[Aram (biblical region)|Aram]], threatened [[Jerusalem]], and [[Ahaz]], [[king of Judah]], appealed to [[Tiglath-Pileser III]], the king of [[Assyria]], for help. After Ahaz paid tribute to Tiglath-Pileser, ({{bibleverse|2|Kings|16:7-9|NIV}}) Tiglath-Pileser sacked Damascus and Israel, annexing Aram<ref name=Grabbe>Lester L. Grabbe, ''Ancient Israel: What Do We Know and How Do We Know It?'' (New York: T&T Clark, 2007): 134</ref> and a large part of Israel, \"including all the land of Naphtali.\" According to {{bibleverse|2|Kings|16:9|NIV}} and {{bibleverse-nb|2|Kings|15:29|NIV}}, the population of Aram and the annexed part of Israel was deported to Assyria. The kingdom of Israel continued to exist until c. 723 BC, when it was again invaded by [[Assyria]] and the rest of the population deported.\n\nFrom that time, the Tribe of Naphtali has been counted as one of the [[Ten Lost Tribes]] of Israel. Psalms 1:24\n\n==Origin==\n[[File:12 Tribes of Israel Map.svg|thumb|right|250px|Map of the 12 tribes of Israel. Naphtali is located in the north.]]\n\nAccording to the [[Torah]], the tribe consisted of descendants of [[Naphtali]], a son of [[Jacob]] and [[Bilhah]], from whom it took its name. However, Arthur Peake views this as a [[postdiction]], an [[eponym]]ous [[metaphor]] providing an [[aetiology]] of the connectedness of the tribe to others in the Israelite confederation.<ref name=\"Peake's commentary on the Bible\">''Peake's Commentary on the Bible''</ref>\n\n==Character==\n[[Militarism]] is featured in Naphtali's history. In the ancient [[Song of Deborah]], Naphtali is commended, along with Zebulun, for risking their lives in the fight against [[Sisera]];<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|5:18|HE}}</ref> in the prose account of the event,<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|4|HE}}</ref> which Arthur Peake regards as a much later narrative based on the poem,<ref name=\"Peake's commentary on the Bible\"/><ref>''Jewish Encyclopedia'', ''Song of Deborah'</ref> there is the addition that [[Barak]], the leader of the anti-Sisera forces, hails from the tribe of Naphtali.<ref>{{bibleverse||Judges|4:6|HE}}</ref> In the [[Gideon]] narrative Naphtali are one of the tribes which join in an attack against [[Midian]]ite invaders, though Arthur Peake regards the Gideon narrative as being spliced together from at least three earlier texts, the oldest of which describes only personal vengeance by Gideon and 300 men of his own clan, not a battle in which the rest of the northern tribes join him.<ref>''Jewish Encyclopedia'', ''Gideon''</ref> In the [[Blessing of Jacob]], which textual scholars date to 700-600 BC - and thus a postdiction, Naphtali is compared to a ''[[deer|hind]] let loose'', and commended for giving ''goodly words''.<ref>{{bibleverse||Genesis|49:21}}</ref>\n\nThe territory allotted to the tribe in [[Canaan]] was in the extreme north, and was bordered on the north by the [[Litani River]], on the east by the [[River Jordan]] until it was {{convert|12|mi|km}} south of the [[Sea of Galilee]], on the west by the tribes of [[Asher]] and [[Zebulun|Zabulon]]; and on the south by the tribe of [[Issachar]].<ref>{{bibleverse||Joshua|19:33-34|HE}} quoted in {{CathEncy|wstitle=Nephtali}}</ref>\nThe symbol of the tribe is a gazelle-a very quick animal. The people of Naftali is traditionally thought of as swift (swift runners).{{Citation needed|date=July 2008}}\n\n==Fate==\nAs part of the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]], during one of the several wars between the Asa of the [[Kingdom of Judah|kingdoms of Judah]] and Baasha of Israel, the tribe of Naphtali was persecuted by [[Ben-Hadad I|Ben-Hadad]], the king of [[Aram-Damascus]], on behalf of [[Asa of Judah|Asa]], the king of Judah, and desolated. Again, in the reign of Pekah this tribe was among the first to feel the iron hand of Assyria and to suffer the deportation of many captives ({{bibleverse|1 Kings|15:20|KJV}}; {{bibleverse|2 Kings|15:20|KJV}}). In a reference to this incident ([[Isaiah 9:1]]\u2013[[Isaiah 9:2|2]]) the prophet Isaiah anticipates that the same region will see the dawn of the Messianic deliverance. Naphtali, one of the most northerly tribes, became one of the first to be conquered. With the land taken, [[Assyrian Exile|the tribe was exiled]]; the manner of their exile led to [[Lost Ten Tribes|their further history being lost]]. One of the famous battles of the Maccabean war was fought near Kedesh-naphtali about B.C. 150, when Jonathan defeated Demetrius, King of Syria ({{bibleverse|1 Maccabees|11:63-73|KJV}}; Josephus, \"Ant.\" xiii. 5, \u00a7 6).{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Descendants==\n\nThere has been speculation that the [[Bukharian Jews]] of Central Asia are the descendants of the Naphtali tribe.<ref>Ehrlich, M. Avrum ''Encyclopedia of the Jewish Diaspora: Origins, Experiences, and Culture'' ABL-CIO October 2008 {{ISBN|978-1-85109-873-6}} p.84 [https://books.google.com/books?id=PF9_EG3VaaUC&pg=PT110&lpg=PT110&dq=Bukharan+lost+tribe+of+naphtali&source=bl&ots=9ufoDz3BBM&sig=eqykSSXjtenxuF5dXlV_TF2kePI&hl=en&ei=LiD2SrD6HpaB8QbUo4jzCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CBsQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=&f=false]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Eastons}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish Lebanese history|Naphtali]]\n[[Category:Jewish Syrian history|Naphtali]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Israel|Naphtali]]\n\n[[th:\u0e40\u0e1c\u0e48\u0e32\u0e19\u0e31\u0e1f\u0e17\u0e32\u0e25\u0e35]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "datalink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tribe_of_Naphtali"}
{"title_page": "Stronghold \u2013 The Collector's Hit Box", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Stronghold \u2013 The Collector's Hit Box\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[Jennifer Rush]]\n| cover      = Stronghold Jennifer Rush.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 31 August 2007\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Sony BMG]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Classics (Jennifer Rush album)|Classics]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Now Is the Hour (Jennifer Rush album)|Now Is the Hour]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n'''''Stronghold \u2013 The Collector's Hit Box''''' is a compilation album by American singer [[Jennifer Rush]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.arcor.de/jennifer-rush-discography/desire-frame.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607202944/http://home.arcor.de/jennifer-rush-discography/desire-frame.html |archive-date=2011-06-07 |df= }}</ref>\n\nReleased in 2007, the collection was widely anticipated by fans. The album came as a 3 [[CD]] [[box set]] featuring single releases, remixes and previously unreleased material.<ref>http://www.jennifer-rush.com/releases/releases_collections.html</ref> Among the rare tracks were four unreleased [[James Bond music|James Bond themes]] that Rush had recorded in the early 1980s before her fame. As well as this, the album featured a new remix of her hit \"I Come Undone\" by Dave Kurtis, which received rave reviews among fans.<ref>http://www.jrc-fancommunity.net/</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = '''Disc One - Hits and Favourites Vol. 1'''\n| extra_column = Album/Single\n| title1 = Ave Maria (Survivors of a Different Kind)\n| length1 = 3:48\n| extra1 = ''[[Movin' (Jennifer Rush album)|Movin]]''\n| title2 = I Come Undone\n| note2 = Extended version\n| length2 = 6:22\n| extra2 = \"I Come Undone\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title3 = Into My Dreams\n| length3 = 4:00\n| extra3 = ''[[Jennifer Rush (1984 album)|Jennifer Rush]]''\n| title4 = Destiny\n| note4 = Extended version\n| length4 = 7:12\n| extra4 = \"Destiny\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title5 = You're My One and Only\n| note5 = Extended version\n| length5 = 4:40\n| extra5 = \"You're My One and Only\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title6 = Call My Name\n| length6 = 4:15\n| extra6 = ''[[Heart over Mind (Jennifer Rush album)|Heart over Mind]]''\n| title7 = Wings of Desire\n| note7 = Extended version\n| length7 = 5:44\n| extra7 = \"Wings of Desire\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title8 = Flames of Paradise <small>(Duet with [[Elton John]])</small>\n| note8 = Extended version\n| length8 = 5:39\n| extra8 = \"Flames of Paradise\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title9 = [[Yester-Me, Yester-You, Yesterday|Yester Me Yester You Yesterday]]\n| note9 = Stevie Wonder cover\n| length9 = 3:15\n| extra9 = ''Movin''\n| title10 = Come Give Me Your Hand\n| length10 = 3:49\n| extra10 = ''Jennifer Rush''\n| title11 = Falling in Love\n| length11 = 3:59\n| extra11 = ''[[Passion (Jennifer Rush album)|Passion]]''\n| title12 = Madonna's Eyes\n| note12 = Extended version\n| length12 = 5:21\n| extra12 = \"Madonna's Eyes\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title13 = Love Get Ready\n| note13 = Extended version\n| length13 = 6:04\n| extra13 = \"Love Get Ready\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title14 = Testify with My Heart\n| length14 = 3:18\n| extra14 = ''Movin''\n| title15 = Love is a Wild Thing\n| length15 = 4:41\n| extra15 = ''[[Wings of Desire (album)|Wings of Desire]]''\n| title16 = [[The Power of Love (Jennifer Rush song)|The Power of Love]]\n| note16 = Extended remix\n| length16 = 7:12\n| extra16 = \"The Power of Love\" <small>(U.K. 12\" single)</small>\n}}\n\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = '''Disc Two - Hits and Favourites Vol. 2'''\n| extra_column = Album/Single\n| title1 = Stronghold\n| length1 = 4:23\n| extra1 = ''Heart over Mind''\n| title2 = 25 Lovers\n| length2 = 3:30\n| extra2 = ''Jennifer Rush''\n| title3 = Heart Over Mind\n| note3 = Extended version\n| length3 = 6:25\n| extra3 = \"Heart over Mind\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title4 = If You're Ever Gonna Lose My Love\n| note4 = Guitar mix\n| length4 = 7:15\n| extra4 = \"If You're Ever Gonna Lose My Love\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title5 = [[Till I Loved You (song)|Till I Loved You]]\n| note5 = Duet with [[Pl\u00e1cido Domingo]]\n| length5 = 4:20\n| extra5 = ''[[Goya: A Life in Song]]''\n| title6 = We are the Strong\n| note6 = Extended version\n| length6 = 5:33\n| extra6 = \"We are the Strong\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title7 = Higher Ground\n| note7 = Extended version\n| length7 = 6:28\n| extra7 = \"Higher Ground\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title8 = Same Heart\n| note8 = Duet with [[Michael Bolton]]\n| length8 = 4:15\n| extra8 = ''Passion''\n| title9 = Heart Wars\n| length9 = 3:13\n| extra9 = ''Heart over Mind''\n| title10 = Midnight Mirage\n| length10 = 4:15\n| extra10 = ''Wings of Desire''\n| title11 = Hero of a Fool\n| note11 = U.S. Album Mix\n| length11 = 3:37\n| extra11 = ''Movin''\n| title12 = Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\n| note12 = Extended version\n| length12 = 6:27\n| extra12 = \"Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title13 = Down to You\n| length13 = 4:27\n| extra13 = ''Heart over Mind''\n| title14 = Ring of Ice\n| note14 = Extended mix\n| length14 = 6:18\n| extra14 = \"Ring of Ice\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title15 = When I Look in Your Eyes\n| length15 = 3:19\n| extra15 = ''Passion''\n| title16 = Where Can You Run\n| length16 = 3:20\n| extra16 = ''Wings of Desire'' <small>(CD bonus track)</small>\n}}\n\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = '''Disc Three - Specials and Rarities'''\n| extra_column = Album/Single\n| title1 = Tonight\n| note1 = As Heidi Stern\n| length1 = 3:16\n| extra1 = \"Tonight\" <small>(Standalone single)</small>\n| title2 = Listen (to What I Say)\n| note2 = As Heidi Stern\n| length2 = 1:46\n| extra2 = \"Tonight\" <small>(B-Side)</small>\n| title3 = [[Goldfinger (song)|Goldfinger]]\n| note3 = [[Shirley Bassey]] cover\n| length3 = 2:58\n| extra3 = ''The Berlin Filmharmonic Concerts'' (1987)\n| title4 = [[The Man with the Golden Gun (song)|The Man with the Golden Gun]]\n| note4 = [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] cover\n| length4 = 2:32\n| extra4 = ''The Berlin Filmharmonic Concerts'' (1987)\n| title5 = [[For Your Eyes Only (Sheena Easton song)|For Your Eyes Only]]\n| note5 = [[Sheena Easton]] cover\n| length5 = 3:03\n| extra5 = ''The Berlin Filmharmonic Concerts'' (1987)\n| title6 = [[Thunderball (soundtrack)|Thunderball]]\n| note6 = [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] cover\n| length6 = 3:01\n| extra6 = ''The Berlin Filmharmonic Concerts'' (1987)\n| title7 = Give Out\n| length7 = 3:18\n| extra7 = \"Into My Dreams\" <small>(B-Side)</small> & \"Ring of Ice\" <small>(German 12\" single)</small>\n| title8 = [[The Witch Queen of New Orleans|Witch Queen of New Orleans]]\n| note8 = [[Redbone (band)|Redbone]] cover\n| length8 = 3:45\n| extra8 = \"Come Give Me Your Hand\" <small>(B-Side)</small>\n| title9 = The Power of Love\n| note9 = Radio Edit\n| length9 = 4:54\n| extra9 = \"The Power of Love\" <small>(7\" Promo & 1995 CD re-release)</small>\n| title10 = Ring of Ice\n| note10 = Extended UK remix\n| length10 = 5:20\n| extra10 = \"Ring of Ice\" <small>(U.K. 12\" single)</small>\n| title11 = Heart Over Mind\n| note11 = Single mix\n| length11 = 4:04\n| extra11 = \"Heart over Mind\" <small>(single)</small>\n| title12 = Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\n| note12 = Club mix\n| length12 = 6:42\n| extra12 = \"Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title13 = Another Day\n| note13 = Japan only single\n| length13 = 4:30\n| extra13 = ''Another Way'' <small>(Soundtrack)</small>\n| title14 = We are the Strong\n| note14 = Single version\n| length14 = 4:02\n| extra14 = \"We are the Strong\" <small>(single)</small>\n| title15 = Si Tu Eres Mi Hombre Y Yo Tu Mujer\n| note15 = The Power of Love\n| length15 = 5:15\n| extra15 = \"The Power of Love\" <small>(Spanish single)</small>\n| title16 = No Me Canso De Pensar En Ti\n| note16 = If You're Ever Gonna Lose My Love\n| length16 = 4:00\n| extra16 = \"If You're Ever Gonna Lose My Love\" <small>(Spanish single)</small>\n| title17 = Vida de Mi Vida\n| note17 = You're My One and Only\n| length17 = 4:30\n| extra17 = \"You're My One and Only\" <small>(Spanish single)</small>\n| title18 = Solitaria Mujer\n| note18 = Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\n| length18 = 4:53\n| extra18 = \"Keep All the Fires Burning Bright\" <small>(Spanish single)</small>\n| title19 = We are the Strong\n| note19 = Soundtrack version\n| length19 = 5:29\n| extra19 = ''Fire, Ice & Dynamite'' <small>(Soundtrack)</small>\n| title20 = I Come Undone\n| note20 = Dave Kurtis remix 2007\n| length20 = 3:21\n| extra20 = Previously Unreleased\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{discogs master|1067301|Stronghold (The Collector's Hit Box)|type=album}}\n\n{{Jennifer Rush}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stronghold - The Collector's Hit Box}}\n[[Category:2007 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Jennifer Rush albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Stronghold \u2013 The Collector's Hit Box\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[Jennifer Rush]]\n| cover      = Stronghold Jennifer Rush.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 31 August 2007\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Sony BMG]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Classics (Jennifer Rush album)|Classics]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Now Is the Hour (Jennifer Rush album)|Now Is the Hour]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n'''''Stronghold \u2013 The Collector's Hit Box''''' is a compilation album by American singer [[Jennifer Rush]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home.arcor.de/jennifer-rush-discography/desire-frame.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-09-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607202944/http://home.arcor.de/jennifer-rush-discography/desire-frame.html |archive-date=2011-06-07 |df= }}</ref>\n\nReleased in 2007, the collection was widely anticipated by fans. The album came as a 3 [[CD]] [[box set]] featuring single releases, remixes and previously unreleased material.<ref>http://www.jennifer-rush.com/releases/releases_collections.html</ref> Among the rare tracks were four unreleased [[James Bond music|James Bond themes]] that Rush had recorded in the early 1980s before her fame. As well as this, the album featured a new remix of her hit \"I Come Undone\" by Dave Kurtis, which received rave reviews among fans.<ref>http://www.jrc-fancommunity.net/</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = '''Disc One - Hits and Favourites Vol. 1'''\n| extra_column = Album/Single\n| title1 = Ave Maria (Survivors of a Different Kind)\n| length1 = 3:48\n| extra1 = ''[[Movin' (Jennifer Rush album)|Movin]]''\n| title2 = I Come Undone\n| note2 = Extended version\n| length2 = 6:22\n| extra2 = \"I Come Undone\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title3 = Into My Dreams\n| length3 = 4:00\n| extra3 = ''[[Jennifer Rush (1984 album)|Jennifer Rush]]''\n| title4 = Destiny\n| note4 = Extended version\n| length4 = 7:12\n| extra4 = \"Destiny\" <small>(12\" single)</small>\n| title5 = You're My One and Only\n| note5 = Extended version\n| length5 = 4:40\n| extra5 = \"You're My One and Only\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title6 = Call My Name\n| length6 = 4:15\n| extra6 = ''[[Heart over Mind (Jennifer Rush album)|Heart over Mind]]''\n| title7 = Wings of Desire\n| note7 = Extended version\n| length7 = 5:44\n| extra7 = \"Wings of Desire\" <small>(12\" & CD singles)</small>\n| title8 = Flames of Paradise <small>(Duet with [[Elton John]])</small>\n| note8 = Extended version\n| length8 = 5:39\n| extra8 = \"Flames of Paradise\" <small