{"title_page": "Chloral hydrate", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 443513096\n| Name = \n| ImageFile = \n| ImageFile1 = Chloral hydrate.svg\n| ImageSize1 = 140px\n| ImageFile2 = Chloral hydrate ball-and-stick model.png\n| ImageSize2 = 140px\n| PIN = 2,2,2-Trichloroethane-1,1-diol\n| SystematicName = \n| OtherNames = Trichloroacetaldehyde monohydrate<br />'''Tradenames:''' Aquachloral, Novo-Chlorhydrate, Somnos, Noctec, Somnote\n| IUPACName = \n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 418M5916WG\n| InChIKey = RNFNDJAIBTYOQL-UHFFFAOYAY\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 455917\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C2H3Cl3O2/c3-2(4,5)1(6)7/h1,6-7H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = RNFNDJAIBTYOQL-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 302-17-0\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 2606\n| PubChem = 2707\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG = D00265\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank = DB01563\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 28142\n| SMILES = ClC(Cl)(Cl)C(O)O\n| InChI=1/C2H3Cl3O2/c3-2(4,5)1(6)7/h1,6-7H\n| EINECS = 206-117-5\n| RTECS = FM875000\n }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=2 | H=3 | Cl=3 | O=2\n| Appearance = Colorless solid\n| Odor = Aromatic, slightly acrid\n| Density = 1.9081 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 57\n| BoilingPtC = 98\n| pKa=9.66, 11.0<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Gawron |first1=O. |last2=Draus |first2=F.|title= Kinetic Evidence for Reaction of Chloralate Ion with ''p''-Nitrophenyl Acetate in Aqueous Solution | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | year = 1958 | volume = 80 | pages = 5392\u20135394 | doi = 10.1021/ja01553a018 | issue = 20}}</ref>\n| Solubility = 660 g/100 ml<ref>{{cite web |title=Chemical Book: Chloral hydrate |url=http://www.chemicalbook.com/ProductChemicalPropertiesCB0198709_EN.htm |accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref>\n| SolubleOther = Very soluble in [[benzene]], [[ethyl ether]], [[ethanol]]\n| LogP = 0.99\n }}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = Monoclinic\n }}\n| Section4 = \n| Section5 = \n| Section6 = {{Chembox Pharmacology\n| ATCCode_prefix = N05\n| ATCCode_suffix = CC01\n| AdminRoutes = Oral syrup, rectal [[suppository]]\n| Bioavail = Well absorbed\n| Metabolism = [[Liver|Hepatic]] and [[Kidney|renal]] (converted to [[2,2,2-Trichloroethanol|trichloroethanol]])\n| HalfLife = 8\u201310 hours\n| ProteinBound =\n| Excretion = Bile, feces, urine (various metabolites not unchanged)\n| Legal_status =\n| Legal_US = Schedule IV\n| Legal_UK =\n| Legal_AU =\n| Legal_CA = Unscheduled\n| Pregnancy_category =\n| Pregnancy_AU =\n| Pregnancy_US = C}}\n| Section7 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| ExternalSDS = [http://www.pcl.ox.ac.uk/MSDS/CH/chloral_hydrate.html External MSDS]{{Dead link|date=December 2019}}\n| EUClass = Harmful ('''Xn''')\n| MainHazards =\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n| RPhrases = {{R22}} {{R36}} {{R37}} {{R38}}\n| LD50 = 1100 mg/kg (mouse, oral)\n }}\n| Section8 = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherCompounds = [[Chloral]], [[chlorobutanol]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Chloral hydrate''' is a [[geminal diol]] with the [[chemical formula|formula]] {{chem2|auto=1|C2H3Cl3O2}}. It is a colorless solid. It has limited use as a [[sedative]] and [[hypnotic]] [[pharmaceutical drug]]. It is also a useful laboratory [[chemical reagent]] and precursor. It is derived from [[chloral]] (trichloroacetaldehyde) by the addition of one [[Equivalent (chemistry)|equivalent]] of water.\n\nIt was discovered in 1832 by [[Justus von Liebig]] in [[Gie\u00dfen]] when a chlorination ([[halogenation]]) reaction was performed on [[ethanol]].<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Ueber die Zersetzung des Alkohols durch Chlor\n|trans-title=On the degradation of alcohol by chlorine\n| authorlink = Justus Liebig | first1 = Justus | last1 = Liebig\n| journal = Annalen der Pharmacie\n| volume = 1\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 31\u201332\n| year = 1832\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_-02AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| doi = 10.1002/jlac.18320010109}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Ueber die Verbindungen, welche durch die Einwirkung des Chlors auf Alkohol, Aether, \u00f6lbildendes Gas und Essiggeist entstehen\n|trans-title=On compounds that arise by the reaction of chlorine with alcohol, oil-forming gas [ethane], and acetone\n| author = Justus Liebig\n| journal = Annalen der Pharmacie\n| volume = 1\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 182\u2013230\n| year = 1832\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_-02AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA182#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| doi = 10.1002/jlac.18320010203}}</ref> Its [[sedative]] properties were observed by [[Rudolf Buchheim]] in 1861, but only described in detail and published by [[Oscar Liebreich]] in 1869;<ref>{{cite journal | jstor = 44450759 | title = The Introduction of Chloral Hydrate into Medical Practice | journal = Bulletin of the History of Medicine | volume = 44 | issue = 2 | pages = 168\u2013172 | last1 = Butler | first1 = Thomas C. | year = 1970 }}</ref> subsequently, because of its easy synthesis, its use became widespread.<ref>{{cite book\n| author = Liebreich, Oskar\n| title = Das Chloralhydrat : ein neues Hypnoticum und Anaestheticum und dessen Anwendung in der Medicin; eine Arzneimittel-Untersuchung\n| url = https://archive.org/details/daschloralhydra00liebgoog\n|trans-title=Chloral Hydrate: A new hypnotic and anaesthetic and its use in medicine; A drug study\n| year = 1869\n| publisher = M\u00fcller\n| location= Berlin}}</ref> It was widely used for sedation in asylums and in general medical practice, and also became a popular drug of abuse in the late 19th century. One notable recreational user, for instance, was the poet and illustrator [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]. Chloral hydrate is soluble in both water and ethanol, readily forming concentrated solutions. A solution of chloral hydrate in ethanol called \"knockout drops\" was used to prepare a [[Mickey Finn (drugs)|Mickey Finn]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/concern/chloral_hydrate.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511075531/http://www.justice.gov/dea/concern/chloral_hydrate.html | archivedate=11 May 2012 | title=Chloral Hydrate | publisher=Drug Enforcement Administration | accessdate=27 June 2018 }}</ref> More reputable uses of chloral hydrate include as a clearing agent for [[chitin]] and fibers and as a key ingredient in [[#Hoyer's mounting medium|Hoyer's mounting medium]], which is used to prepare permanent or semipermanent [[microscope slide]]s of small organisms, [[histological section]]s, and [[chromosome squash]]es. Because of its status as a regulated substance, chloral hydrate can be difficult to obtain. This has led to chloral hydrate being replaced by alternative reagents<ref>{{cite journal | title = An Improved Clearing and Mounting Solution to Replace Chloral Hydrate in Microscopic Applications | journal = Applications in Plant Sciences |volume=1 |issue=5 | doi=10.3732/apps.1300016 | pmid = 25202549 | pages=1300016|year = 2013|last1 = Villani|first1 = Thomas S.| last2 = Koroch | first2 = Adolfina R. | last3 = Simon | first3 = James E. | pmc = 4105042 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Pyrrole Alkaloids with Potential Cancer Chemopreventive Activity Isolated from a Goji Berry-Contaminated Commercial Sample of African Mango | journal = Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |volume=62 |issue=22 |pages=5054\u20135060| doi=10.1021/jf500802x | pmid=24792835 | pmc=4047925 | last1 = Li | first1 = J. | last2 = Pan | first2 = L. | last3 = Naman | first3 = C. B. | last4 = Deng | first4 = Y. | last5 = Chai | first5 = H. | last6 = Keller | first6 = W. J. | last7 = Kinghorn | first7 = A. D. |year = 2014}}</ref> in microscopy procedures.\n\nIt is, together with [[chloroform]], a minor [[side-product]] of the [[Water chlorination|chlorination]] of water when organic residues such as [[humic acids]] are present. It has been detected in drinking water at concentrations of up to 100 [[microgram]]s per litre (\u00b5g/L) but concentrations are normally found to be below 10&nbsp;\u00b5g/L. Levels are generally found to be higher in [[surface water]] than in [[ground water]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/dwq/chemicals/chloralhydratesumstatement.pdf | title=Summary statement - 12.20 Chloral hydrate (trichloroacetaldehyde) | publisher=World Health Organization | accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate has not been approved by the [[US Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] in the [[United States]] or the [[European Medicines Agency|EMA]] in the [[European Union]] for any [[Indication (medicine)|medical indication]] and is on the FDA list of unapproved drugs that are still prescribed by clinicians.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meadows |first1=Michelle |title=The FDA Takes Action Against Unapproved Drugs |journal=FDA Consumer Magazine |date=January\u2013February 2007 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/65c5/3eef8c415cc0b6a918d61c2bf2d7318742d8.pdf |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref> Usage of the drug as a sedative or hypnotic may carry some risk given the lack of [[clinical trial]]s. However, chloral hydrate products, licensed for short-term management of severe insomnia, are available in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/search?q=chloral+hydrate | title=EMC Search: chloral hydrate | publisher=Electronic Medicines Compendium | accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n===Hypnotic===\nChloral hydrate is used for the short-term treatment of [[insomnia]] and as a sedative before minor medical or dental treatment. It was largely displaced in the mid-20th century by [[barbiturate]]s<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tariq | first1 = Syed H. | last2 = Pulisetty | first2 = Shailaja | year = 2008 | title = Pharmacotherapy for Insomnia | url = | journal = Clinics in Geriatric Medicine | volume = 24 | issue = 1| pages = 93\u2013105 | doi = 10.1016/j.cger.2007.08.009 | pmid = 18035234 }}</ref> and subsequently by [[benzodiazepine]]s. It was also formerly used in veterinary medicine as a [[general anesthetic]] but is not considered acceptable for anesthesia or euthanasia of small animals due to adverse effects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baxter|first=Mark G.|last2=Murphy|first2=Kathy L.|last3=Taylor|first3=Polly M.|last4=Wolfensohn|first4=Sarah E.|date=July 2009|title=Chloral Hydrate Is Not Acceptable for Anesthesia or Euthanasia of Small Animals|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=111|issue=1|pages=209\u2013210|doi=10.1097/aln.0b013e3181a8617e|pmid=19546703|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> It is also still used as a sedative prior to [[Electroencephalography|EEG]] procedures, as it is one of the few available sedatives that does not suppress [[epilepsy|epileptiform]] discharges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jcc.kau.edu.sa/Files/140/Researches/11822_Chloral.pdf|title=The use of chloral hydrate in pediatric electroencephalography|author1=Mohammed M.S. Jan, MBChB, FRCP (C)|author2=Marilou F. Aquino, EEG Tech.|website=Jcc.kau.edu.sa|accessdate=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818213222/http://jcc.kau.edu.sa/Files/140/Researches/11822_Chloral.pdf|archive-date=18 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn therapeutic doses for insomnia, chloral hydrate is effective within 20 to 60 minutes.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Chloral hydrate: a hypnotic best forgotten? |last1=Gauillard |first1=J. |last2=Cheref |first2=S. |last3=Vacherontrystram |first3=M. N. |first4=Martin |last4=J. C. | journal=Encephale |date=May\u2013June 2002 | volume=28 | issue=3 Pt 1 | pages=200\u2013204 | pmid=12091779}}</ref> In humans it is [[Metabolism|metabolized]] within 7 hours into [[trichloroethanol]] and trichloroethanol glucuronide by erythrocytes and plasma esterases and into [[trichloroacetic acid]] in 4 to 5 days.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ntp.niehs.nih.gov/ntp/htdocs/st_rpts/tox059.pdf | title=NTP Technical Report on the Toxicity and Metabolism Studies of Chloral Hydrate | publisher=National Toxicology Program | work=Toxicity Report Series Number 59 | accessdate=14 March 2013 | last=Beland | first=Frederick A. | pages=10}}</ref> It has a very narrow therapeutic window making this drug difficult to use. Higher doses can depress [[Respiration (physiology)|respiration]] and [[blood pressure]].\n\n===In organic synthesis===\nChloral hydrate is a starting point for the synthesis of other organic compounds. It is the starting material for the production of [[chloral]], which is produced by the distillation of a mixture of chloral hydrate and [[sulfuric acid]], which serves as the [[desiccant]].\n\nNotably, it is used to synthesize [[isatin]]. In this synthesis, chloral hydrate reacts with [[aniline]] and [[hydroxylamine]] to give a condensation product which cyclicizes in [[sulfuric acid]] to give the target compound:<ref>{{OrgSynth | title = Isatin | first1 = C. S. | last1 = Marvel | first2 = G. S. | last2 = Hiers | collvol = 1 | collvolpages = 327 | year = 1941 | prep = cv1p0327}}</ref>\n\n:[[File:Synthesis of isatin.svg|450px]]\n\nMoreover, chloral hydrate is used as a reagent for the deprotection of acetals, dithioacetals and tetrahydropyranyl ethers in organic solvents.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chandrasekhar |first1=S. |last2=Shrinidhi |first2=A. |title=Chloral Hydrate as a Water Carrier for the Efficient Deprotection of Acetals, Dithioacetals, and Tetrahydropyranyl Ethers in Organic Solvents |journal=Synthetic Communications |date=2014 |volume=44 |issue=13 |pages=1904\u20131913 |doi=10.1080/00397911.2013.876652}}</ref>\n\n===Botany and mycology===\n====Hoyer's mounting medium====\nChloral hydrate is also an ingredient used for Hoyer's solution, a [[mounting medium]] for microscopic observation of diverse plant types such as [[bryophyte]]s, [[fern]]s, [[seed]]s, and small [[arthropod]]s (especially [[mite]]s). Other ingredients may include [[gum arabic]] and [[glycerol]]. An advantage of this medium includes a high [[refractive index]] and clearing (macerating) properties of small specimens (especially advantageous if specimens require observation with [[differential interference contrast microscopy]]).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n====Melzer's reagent====\nChloral hydrate is an ingredient used to make [[Melzer's reagent]], an [[aqueous solution]] that is used to identify certain species of [[fungi]]. The other ingredients are [[potassium iodide]], and [[iodine]]. Whether tissue or spores react to this reagent is vital for the correct identification of some mushrooms.\n\n==Safety==\nChloral hydrate was routinely administered in gram quantities. Prolonged exposure to the vapors is unhealthy however, with a [[Median lethal dose|LD<sub>50</sub>]] for 4-hour exposure of 440&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>. Long-term use of chloral hydrate is associated with a rapid development of tolerance to its effects and possible addiction as well as adverse effects including rashes, gastric discomfort and severe kidney, heart, and liver failure.<ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Gelder | first1 = M. | last2 = Mayou | first2 = R. | last3 = Geddes | first3 = J. | year = 2005 | title = Psychiatry | edition = 3rd | location = New York | publisher = Oxford | page = 238}}</ref>\n\nAcute overdosage is often characterized by [[nausea]], vomiting, confusion, [[convulsion]]s, slow and irregular breathing, [[cardiac arrhythmia]], and [[coma]]. The [[Blood plasma|plasma]], [[Blood serum|serum]] or [[blood]] concentrations of chloral hydrate and/or trichloroethanol, its major active metabolite, may be measured to confirm a diagnosis of poisoning in hospitalized patients or to aid in the medicolegal investigation of fatalities. Accidental [[Drug overdose|overdosage]] of young children undergoing simple dental or surgical procedures has occurred. [[Hemodialysis]] has been used successfully to accelerate clearance of the drug in poisoning victims.<ref>{{Cite book | first = R. | last = Baselt | title = Disposition of Toxic Drugs and Chemicals in Man | edition = 8th | publisher = Biomedical Publications | location = Foster City, CA | year = 2008 | pages = 259\u2013261}}</ref> It is listed as having a \"conditional risk\" of causing [[torsades de pointes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crediblemeds.org/index.php/drugsearch|title=CredibleMeds :: Quicksearch|website=Crediblemeds.org|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nChloral hydrate is produced from [[chlorine]] and [[ethanol]] in acidic solution. In basic conditions the [[haloform reaction]] takes place and chloral hydrate is [[Chemical decomposition|decomposed]] by [[hydrolysis]] to form [[chloroform]].<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://jhs.pharm.or.jp/data/49%281%29/49_1.pdf | title=A Problem in the Determination of Trihalomethane by Headspace-Gas Chromatography/Mass Spectrometry |last1=Takahashi |first1=Yasuo |last2=Onodera |first2=Sukeo |last3=Morita |first3=Masatoshi |last4=Terao |first4=Yoshiyasu | journal=Journal of Health Science | year=2003 | volume=49 | issue=1 | pages=3 | doi=10.1248/jhs.49.1}}</ref>\n\n:4&nbsp;Cl<sub>2</sub> + C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub>OH + H<sub>2</sub>O \u2192 Cl<sub>3</sub>CCH(OH)<sub>2</sub> + 5&nbsp;HCl\n\n==Pharmacology==\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nChloral hydrate is metabolized ''[[in vivo]]'' to [[trichloroethanol]], which is responsible for secondary physiological and psychological effects.<ref name=Ull>{{Ullmann|first1=Reinhard |last1=Jira |first2=Erwin |last2=Kopp |first3=Blaine C. |last3=McKusick |first4=Gerhard |last4=R\u00f6derer |first5=Axel |last5=Bosch |first6=Gerald |last6=Fleischmann |title=Chloroacetaldehydes |doi=10.1002/14356007.a06_527.pub2}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate is structurally and [[pharmacodynamics | pharmacodynamically]] similar to [[ethchlorvynol]] (Placidyl), a pharmaceutical developed during the 1950s that was marketed as a hypnotic until 1999 when production was voluntarily ceased by manufacturers in favor of benzodiazepines. The metabolite of chloral hydrate exerts its pharmacological properties via enhancing the [[GABA receptor]] complex<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=17557503 |year=2006 |last1=Lu |first1=J. |last2=Greco |first2=M. A. |title=Sleep circuitry and the hypnotic mechanism of GABA<sub>A</sub> drugs |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=S19\u2013S26 |journal=Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine}}</ref> and therefore is similar in action to [[benzodiazepine]]s, [[nonbenzodiazepines]] and [[barbiturates]]. It can be moderately [[Substance use disorder|addictive]], as [[chronic (medicine)|chronic]] use is known to cause [[Chemical dependency|dependency]] and [[Drug withdrawal|withdrawal]] symptoms. The chemical can potentiate various [[anticoagulant]]s and is weakly [[mutagen]]ic ''[[in vitro]]'' and ''in vivo''.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}}\n\n==Legal status==\nIn the United States, chloral hydrate is a [[Controlled Substances Act#Schedule_IV_controlled_substances|schedule IV]] [[controlled substance]] and requires a physician's prescription. Its properties have sometimes led to its use as a [[date rape drug]].<ref name=\"pmid15622794\">{{cite journal |last1= McGregor |first1=M. J. |last2=Ericksen |first2=J. |last3=Ronald |first3=L. A. |last4=Janssen |first4=P. A. |last5=Van Vliet |first5=A. |last6=Schulzer |first6=M. |title=Rising incidence of hospital-reported drug-facilitated sexual assault in a large urban community in Canada. Retrospective population-based study |journal=Canadian Journal of Public Health |volume=95 |issue=6 |pages=441\u2013445 |year=2004 |pmid=15622794 |doi= 10.1007/BF03403990|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/attacked-gang-article-1.305483|title=Attacked by the Gang|website = New York Daily News|date= 25 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nChloral hydrate was first synthesized by the chemist [[Justus von Liebig]] in 1832 at the University of Giessen.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Psychiatry: From the era of the asylum to the age of Prozac|first=Edward|last=Shorter|date=1998|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-0471245315|oclc=60169541}}</ref> Through experimentation physiologist [[Claude Bernard]] clarified that the chloral hydrate was [[hypnotic]] as opposed to an [[analgesic]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Worst of Evils: The fight against pain|first=Thomas|last=Dormandy|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300113228|oclc=878623979|url=https://archive.org/details/worstofevilsmans00dorm}}</ref> It was the first of a long line of sedatives, most notably the [[barbiturate]]s, manufactured and marketed by the German pharmaceutical industry.<ref name=\":0\" /> Historically, chloral hydrate was utilized primarily as a [[psychiatric medication]]. In 1869, German physician and pharmacologist [[Oscar Liebreich]] began to promote its use to calm anxiety, especially when it caused insomnia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Before Prozac: The troubled history of mood disorders in psychiatry|first=Edward|last=Shorter|date=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195368741|oclc=299368559|url=https://archive.org/details/beforeprozactrou00shor}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Chloral hydrate had certain advantages over [[morphine]] for this application, as it worked quickly without injection and had a consistent strength. It achieved wide use in both [[Lunatic asylum|asylums]] and the homes of those socially refined enough to avoid asylums. Upper- and middle-class women, well-represented in the latter category, were particularly susceptible to chloral hydrate [[addiction]]. After the 1904 invention of [[barbital]], the first of the [[barbiturate]] family, chloral hydrate began to disappear from use among those with means.<ref name=\":0\" /> It remained common in asylums and hospitals until the Second World War as it was quite cheap. Chloral hydrate had some other important advantages that kept it in use for five decades despite the existence of more advanced [[barbiturate]]s. It was the safest available sedative until the middle of the twentieth century, and thus was particularly favored for children.<ref name=\":1\" /> It also left patients much more refreshed after a deep sleep than more recently invented sedatives. Its frequency of use made it an early and regular feature in ''[[The Merck Manuals|The Merck Manual]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuadrado|first=Fernando F.|last2=Alston|first2=Theodore A.|date=October 2016|title=Book Review|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=4|pages=153\u2013155|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2016.01.004|issn=2352-4529}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate was also a significant object of study in various early pharmacological experiments. In 1875, [[Claude Bernard]] tried to determine if chloral hydrate exerted its action through a metabolic conversion to [[chloroform]]. This was not only the first attempt to determine whether different drugs were converted to the same [[metabolite]] in the body but also the first to measure the concentration of a particular pharmaceutical in the blood. The results were inconclusive.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alston|first=Theodore A.|date=July 2016|title=Noteworthy Chemistry of Chloroform|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=3|pages=85\u201388|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2016.04.008|pmid=27480474|issn=2352-4529}}</ref> In 1899 and 1901 [[Hans Horst Meyer]] and [[Ernest Overton]] respectively made the major discovery that the [[Theories of general anaesthetic action|general anaesthetic action]] of a drug was strongly correlated to its [[lipid]] [[solubility]]. However, chloral hydrate was quite polar but nonetheless a potent hypnotic. Overton was unable to explain this mystery. Thus, chloral hydrate remained one of the major and persistent exceptions to this breakthrough discovery in pharmacology. This anomaly was eventually resolved in 1948, when Claude Bernard's experiment was repeated. While chloral hydrate was converted to a different metabolite than chloroform, it was found that was converted into the more [[lipophilic]] molecule [[2,2,2-Trichloroethanol]]. This metabolite fit much better with the Meyer\u2013Overton correlation than chloral had. Prior to this, it had not been demonstrated that general anesthetics could undergo chemical changes to exert their action in the body.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krasowski|first=Matthew D.|title=Contradicting a Unitary Theory of General Anesthetic Action: a History of Three Compounds from 1901 to 2001|journal=Bulletin of Anesthesia History|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1016/s1522-8649(03)50031-2|pmid=17494361|pmc=2701367|year=2003}}</ref>\n\nFinally, chloral hydrate was also the first hypnotic to be used [[intravenous injection|intravenously]] as a general anesthetic. In 1871, [[Pierre-Cyprien Or\u00e9]] began experiments on animals, followed by humans. While a state of general anesthesia could be achieved, the technique never caught on because its administration was more complex and less safe than the oral administration of chloral hydrate, and less safe for intravenous use than later general anesthetics were found to be.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Matthew|last2=Jagdish|first2=S.|date=January 2016|title=A History of Intravenous Anesthesia in War (1656\u20131988)|url=http://www.anesthesiahistoryjournal.org/article/S2352-4529(15)00084-5/fulltext|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=1|pages=13\u201321|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2015.10.007|pmid=26898141|issn=2352-4529}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nChloral hydrate was used as one of the earliest synthetic drugs to treat [[insomnia]] until 1912, when [[phenobarbital]] replaced it and made its use unnecessary.\n\nIn 1897, [[Bram Stoker]]'s [[epistolary novel]] ''[[Dracula]]'', one of its characters, Doctor [[John Seward]], recorded his use and his [[molecular formula]] in his [[phonograph]]ic [[diary]]:\n\n<blockquote>I cannot but think of Lucy, and how different things might have been. If I don't sleep at once, chloral, the modern [[Morpheus]]\u2014 C<sub>2</sub>HCl<sub>3</sub>O&nbsp;.&nbsp;H<sub>2</sub>O! I should be careful not to let it grow into a habit. No I shall take none to-night! I have thought of Lucy, and I shall not dishonor her by mixing the two.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/draculabr00stokuoft|title=Dracula|first=Bram|last=Stoker|date=28 February 1897|publisher=New York Grosset & Dunlap|accessdate=28 February 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the conclusion of [[Edith Wharton]]'s 1905 novel ''[[The House of Mirth]]'', Lily Bart, the novel's heroine, becomes addicted to chloral hydrate and overdoses on the substance:\n<blockquote>She put out her hand and measured the soothing drops into a glass; but as she did so, she knew they would be powerless against the supernatural lucidity of her brain. She had long since raised the dose to its highest limit, but to-night she felt she must increase it. She knew she took a slight risk in doing so; she remembered the chemist's warning. If sleep came at all, it might be a sleep without waking.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/284/284-h/284-h.htm#chap0213|title=House of Mirth|website=www.gutenberg.org|access-date=2 July 2018|date=June 1995}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the third season of the HBO drama series ''[[Oz (TV series)|Oz]]'', the drug is used by inmate [[Ryan O'Reily]] to aid his brother, [[Cyril O'Reily]], during a boxing tournament by sneaking the drug into his opponent's drinking bottles, slowing the fighter down and allowing for Cyril to win his fights.\n\n==Notable users==\n*[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]] (1828\u20131882) became addicted to chloral, with whisky chasers, after the death of his wife [[Elizabeth Siddal]] from a [[laudanum]] overdose in 1862. He had a mental breakdown in 1872. He lived out the last ten years of his life addicted to chloral and alcohol, in part to mask the pain of botched surgery to an enlarged testicle in 1877.\n* Irish physicist [[John Tyndall]] (1820\u20131893) died of an accidental overdose of chloral administered by his wife.\n* Psychologist and philosopher [[William James]] (1842-1910) who used the drug for insomnia and sedation due to chronic neurosis.\n* [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] (1844\u20131900) regularly used chloral hydrate in the years leading up to his nervous breakdown, according to Lou Salome and other associates. Whether the drug contributed to his insanity is a point of controversy.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cate |first=Curtis |title=Friedrich Nietzsche |publisher=[[The Overlook Press]] |year=2005 |place=Woodstock, NY|ref=harv|page=453}}</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] (1869\u20131951) was given chloral hydrate as a boy for sleep problems by a physician named Lizart. Gide states in his autobiography ''[[Si le grain ne meurt|If It Die...]]'' that \"all my later weaknesses of will or memory I attribute to him.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Gide|first=Andr\u00e9|authorlink=Andr\u00e9 Gide|translator-first=Dorothy|translator-last=Bussey|title=If It Die...An Autobiography|location=New York|publisher=Vintage International|orig-year=1924|date=2001|page=105}}</ref>\n*[[Evelyn Waugh]] (1903-1966), insomniac for much of his adult life, for which 'in later life ... he became so deleteriously dependent on chloral'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hastings|first=Selina|title=Evelyn Waugh: A Biography|publisher=Sinclair-Stevenson|year=1994|isbn=1 85619 223 7|location=|pages=140}}</ref>  Waugh's novel, ''[[The Ordeal of Gilbert Pinfold]]'', is largely a fictionalised account of an episode Waugh himself experienced as a result of excessive use of chloral in combination with bromide and alcohol.  Waugh's friend and biographer [[Christopher Sykes (author)|Christopher Sykes]] observed that Waugh's description of [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti|D.G. Rossetti]]'s demise under the effects of excessive use of chloral in his 1928 biography of the artist 'is a fairly exact description of how [Waugh's own] life ended in 1966'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sykes|first=Christopher|title=Evelyn Waugh: A Biography|publisher=Penguin Books|year=1977|isbn=|location=|pages=124}}</ref>\n* [[Marilyn Monroe]] (1926\u20131962) died from an overdose of chloral hydrate and [[pentobarbital]] (Nembutal).<ref>{{Cite book | last = Banner | first = Lois | title = Marilyn: The Passion and the Paradox | year = 2012 | publisher = Bloomsbury | isbn = 978-1-40883-133-5 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/marilynpassionpa0000bann/page/411 411\u2013412] | url = https://archive.org/details/marilynpassionpa0000bann/page/411 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last=Spoto | first=Donald | title=Marilyn Monroe: The Biography | publisher=Cooper Square Press | year=2001 | isbn=978-0-8154-1183-3 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/marilynmonroe00dona/page/580 580\u2013583] | url=https://archive.org/details/marilynmonroe00dona/page/580 }}</ref>\n* [[Oliver Sacks]] (1933\u20132015) abused chloral hydrate in 1965 as a depressed insomniac. He found himself taking fifteen times the usual dose of chloral hydrate every night before he eventually ran out, causing violent withdrawal symptoms.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sacks|first=Oliver|title=Altered States|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/08/27/altered-states-3 |work=The New Yorker |date=27 August 2012|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Jonestown|The Jonestown mass murder-suicides]] in 1978, involved the communal drinking of [[Flavor Aid]] poisoned with [[diazepam|Valium]], chloral hydrate, [[potassium cyanide|cyanide]], and [[Phenergan]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hall|first1=John R.|title=Gone from the Promised Land: Jonestown in American Cultural History|date=1987|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9780887388019|page=282|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D8MCb1xqqo8C&pg=PA282|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Hank Williams]] (1923\u20131953) died from a combination of chloral hydrate, [[morphine]] and [[whiskey]].<ref>{{Harvnb|\n Olson, Ted |2004|p= 296}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb| Olson, Ted| 2004| p= 298}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |author= Lilly, John|title= Hank's Lost Charleston Show|publisher= West Virginia Division of Culture and History}}</ref>\n* [[Montgomery Clift]]<ref>Brando, Marlon; Lindsey, Robert (1994). Songs my mother taught me. New York: Random House. {{ISBN|978-0-09-943691-1}}.</ref>\n* [[Anna Nicole Smith]] (1967\u20132007) died of \"[[combined drug intoxication]]\" with [[chloral hydrate]] as the \"major component.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070326/ap_on_en_tv/anna_nicole_smith |title=Smith died from accidental drug overdose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331213201/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070326/ap_on_en_tv/anna_nicole_smith |archivedate=31 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chlorobutanol]]\n* [[Disulfiram-like drug]]\n* [[Trichloroethanol]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Chloral hydrate}}\n\n{{Sedative|state=collapsed}}\n{{GABAAR PAMs}}\n{{Glycinergics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chloral Hydrate}}\n[[Category:Acetaldehyde dehydrogenase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Aldehydes]]\n[[Category:GABAA receptor positive allosteric modulators]]\n[[Category:Glycine receptor agonists]]\n[[Category:Hydrates]]\n[[Category:Hypnotics]]\n[[Category:Sedatives]]\n[[Category:Organochlorides]]\n[[Category:Prodrugs]]\n[[Category:Trichloromethyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Geminal diols]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 443513096\n| Name = \n| ImageFile = \n| ImageFile1 = Chloral hydrate.svg\n| ImageSize1 = 140px\n| ImageFile2 = Chloral hydrate ball-and-stick model.png\n| ImageSize2 = 140px\n| PIN = 2,2,2-Trichloroethane-1,1-diol\n| SystematicName = \n| OtherNames = Trichloroacetaldehyde monohydrate<br />'''Tradenames:''' Aquachloral, Novo-Chlorhydrate, Somnos, Noctec, Somnote\n| IUPACName = \n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 418M5916WG\n| InChIKey = RNFNDJAIBTYOQL-UHFFFAOYAY\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 455917\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C2H3Cl3O2/c3-2(4,5)1(6)7/h1,6-7H\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = RNFNDJAIBTYOQL-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 302-17-0\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 2606\n| PubChem = 2707\n| KEGG_Ref = {{keggcite|correct|kegg}}\n| KEGG = D00265\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank = DB01563\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 28142\n| SMILES = ClC(Cl)(Cl)C(O)O\n| InChI=1/C2H3Cl3O2/c3-2(4,5)1(6)7/h1,6-7H\n| EINECS = 206-117-5\n| RTECS = FM875000\n }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=2 | H=3 | Cl=3 | O=2\n| Appearance = Colorless solid\n| Odor = Aromatic, slightly acrid\n| Density = 1.9081 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 57\n| BoilingPtC = 98\n| pKa=9.66, 11.0<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Gawron |first1=O. |last2=Draus |first2=F.|title= Kinetic Evidence for Reaction of Chloralate Ion with ''p''-Nitrophenyl Acetate in Aqueous Solution | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | year = 1958 | volume = 80 | pages = 5392\u20135394 | doi = 10.1021/ja01553a018 | issue = 20}}</ref>\n| Solubility = 660 g/100 ml<ref>{{cite web |title=Chemical Book: Chloral hydrate |url=http://www.chemicalbook.com/ProductChemicalPropertiesCB0198709_EN.htm |accessdate=27 February 2017 }}</ref>\n| SolubleOther = Very soluble in [[benzene]], [[ethyl ether]], [[ethanol]]\n| LogP = 0.99\n }}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Structure\n| CrystalStruct = Monoclinic\n }}\n| Section4 = \n| Section5 = \n| Section6 = {{Chembox Pharmacology\n| ATCCode_prefix = N05\n| ATCCode_suffix = CC01\n| AdminRoutes = Oral syrup, rectal [[suppository]]\n| Bioavail = Well absorbed\n| Metabolism = [[Liver|Hepatic]] and [[Kidney|renal]] (converted to [[2,2,2-Trichloroethanol|trichloroethanol]])\n| HalfLife = 8\u201310 hours\n| ProteinBound =\n| Excretion = Bile, feces, urine (various metabolites not unchanged)\n| Legal_status =\n| Legal_US = Schedule IV\n| Legal_UK =\n| Legal_AU =\n| Legal_CA = Unscheduled\n| Pregnancy_category =\n| Pregnancy_AU =\n| Pregnancy_US = C}}\n| Section7 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| ExternalSDS = [http://www.pcl.ox.ac.uk/MSDS/CH/chloral_hydrate.html External MSDS]{{Dead link|date=December 2019}}\n| EUClass = Harmful ('''Xn''')\n| MainHazards =\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n| RPhrases = {{R22}} {{R36}} {{R37}} {{R38}}\n| LD50 = 1100 mg/kg (mouse, oral)\n }}\n| Section8 = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherCompounds = [[Chloral]], [[chlorobutanol]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Chloral hydrate''' is a [[geminal diol]] with the [[chemical formula|formula]] {{chem2|auto=1|C2H3Cl3O2}}. It is a colorless solid. It has limited use as a [[sedative]] and [[hypnotic]] [[pharmaceutical drug]]. It is also a useful laboratory [[chemical reagent]] and precursor. It is derived from [[chloral]] (trichloroacetaldehyde) by the addition of one [[Equivalent (chemistry)|equivalent]] of water.\n\nIt was discovered in 1832 by [[Justus von Liebig]] in [[Gie\u00dfen]] when a chlorination ([[halogenation]]) reaction was performed on [[ethanol]].<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Ueber die Zersetzung des Alkohols durch Chlor\n|trans-title=On the degradation of alcohol by chlorine\n| authorlink = Justus Liebig | first1 = Justus | last1 = Liebig\n| journal = Annalen der Pharmacie\n| volume = 1\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 31\u201332\n| year = 1832\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_-02AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| doi = 10.1002/jlac.18320010109}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Ueber die Verbindungen, welche durch die Einwirkung des Chlors auf Alkohol, Aether, \u00f6lbildendes Gas und Essiggeist entstehen\n|trans-title=On compounds that arise by the reaction of chlorine with alcohol, oil-forming gas [ethane], and acetone\n| author = Justus Liebig\n| journal = Annalen der Pharmacie\n| volume = 1\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 182\u2013230\n| year = 1832\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_-02AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA182#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| doi = 10.1002/jlac.18320010203}}</ref> Its [[sedative]] properties were observed by [[Rudolf Buchheim]] in 1861, but only described in detail and published by [[Oscar Liebreich]] in 1869;<ref>{{cite journal | jstor = 44450759 | title = The Introduction of Chloral Hydrate into Medical Practice | journal = Bulletin of the History of Medicine | volume = 44 | issue = 2 | pages = 168\u2013172 | last1 = Butler | first1 = Thomas C. | year = 1970 }}</ref> subsequently, because of its easy synthesis, its use became widespread.<ref>{{cite book\n| author = Liebreich, Oskar\n| title = Das Chloralhydrat : ein neues Hypnoticum und Anaestheticum und dessen Anwendung in der Medicin; eine Arzneimittel-Untersuchung\n| url = https://archive.org/details/daschloralhydra00liebgoog\n|trans-title=Chloral Hydrate: A new hypnotic and anaesthetic and its use in medicine; A drug study\n| year = 1869\n| publisher = M\u00fcller\n| location= Berlin}}</ref> It was widely used for sedation in asylums and in general medical practice, and also became a popular drug of abuse in the late 19th century. One notable recreational user, for instance, was the poet and illustrator [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]. Chloral hydrate is soluble in both water and ethanol, readily forming concentrated solutions. A solution of chloral hydrate in ethanol called \"knockout drops\" was used to prepare a [[Mickey Finn (drugs)|Mickey Finn]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/concern/chloral_hydrate.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511075531/http://www.justice.gov/dea/concern/chloral_hydrate.html | archivedate=11 May 2012 | title=Chloral Hydrate | publisher=Drug Enforcement Administration | accessdate=27 June 2018 }}</ref> More reputable uses of chloral hydrate include as a clearing agent for [[chitin]] and fibers and as a key ingredient in [[#Hoyer's mounting medium|Hoyer's mounting medium]], which is used to prepare permanent or semipermanent [[microscope slide]]s of small organisms, [[histological section]]s, and [[chromosome squash]]es. Because of its status as a regulated substance, chloral hydrate can be difficult to obtain. This has led to chloral hydrate being replaced by alternative reagents<ref>{{cite journal | title = An Improved Clearing and Mounting Solution to Replace Chloral Hydrate in Microscopic Applications | journal = Applications in Plant Sciences |volume=1 |issue=5 | doi=10.3732/apps.1300016 | pmid = 25202549 | pages=1300016|year = 2013|last1 = Villani|first1 = Thomas S.| last2 = Koroch | first2 = Adolfina R. | last3 = Simon | first3 = James E. | pmc = 4105042 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Pyrrole Alkaloids with Potential Cancer Chemopreventive Activity Isolated from a Goji Berry-Contaminated Commercial Sample of African Mango | journal = Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry |volume=62 |issue=22 |pages=5054\u20135060| doi=10.1021/jf500802x | pmid=24792835 | pmc=4047925 | last1 = Li | first1 = J. | last2 = Pan | first2 = L. | last3 = Naman | first3 = C. B. | last4 = Deng | first4 = Y. | last5 = Chai | first5 = H. | last6 = Keller | first6 = W. J. | last7 = Kinghorn | first7 = A. D. |year = 2014}}</ref> in microscopy procedures.\n\nIt is, together with [[chloroform]], a minor [[side-product]] of the [[Water chlorination|chlorination]] of water when organic residues such as [[humic acids]] are present. It has been detected in drinking water at concentrations of up to 100 [[microgram]]s per litre (\u00b5g/L) but concentrations are normally found to be below 10&nbsp;\u00b5g/L. Levels are generally found to be higher in [[surface water]] than in [[ground water]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/dwq/chemicals/chloralhydratesumstatement.pdf | title=Summary statement - 12.20 Chloral hydrate (trichloroacetaldehyde) | publisher=World Health Organization | accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate has not been approved by the [[US Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] in the [[United States]] or the [[European Medicines Agency|EMA]] in the [[European Union]] for any [[Indication (medicine)|medical indication]] and is on the FDA list of unapproved drugs that are still prescribed by clinicians.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Meadows |first1=Michelle |title=The FDA Takes Action Against Unapproved Drugs |journal=FDA Consumer Magazine |date=January\u2013February 2007 |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/65c5/3eef8c415cc0b6a918d61c2bf2d7318742d8.pdf |accessdate=13 July 2018}}</ref> Usage of the drug as a sedative or hypnotic may carry some risk given the lack of [[clinical trial]]s. However, chloral hydrate products, licensed for short-term management of severe insomnia, are available in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.medicines.org.uk/emc/search?q=chloral+hydrate | title=EMC Search: chloral hydrate | publisher=Electronic Medicines Compendium | accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n===Hypnotic===\nChloral hydrate is used for the short-term treatment of [[insomnia]] and as a sedative before minor medical or dental treatment. It was largely displaced in the mid-20th century by [[barbiturate]]s<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tariq | first1 = Syed H. | last2 = Pulisetty | first2 = Shailaja | year = 2008 | title = Pharmacotherapy for Insomnia | url = | journal = Clinics in Geriatric Medicine | volume = 24 | issue = 1| pages = 93\u2013105 | doi = 10.1016/j.cger.2007.08.009 | pmid = 18035234 }}</ref> and subsequently by [[benzodiazepine]]s. It was also formerly used in veterinary medicine as a [[general anesthetic]] but is not considered acceptable for anesthesia or euthanasia of small animals due to adverse effects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baxter|first=Mark G.|last2=Murphy|first2=Kathy L.|last3=Taylor|first3=Polly M.|last4=Wolfensohn|first4=Sarah E.|date=July 2009|title=Chloral Hydrate Is Not Acceptable for Anesthesia or Euthanasia of Small Animals|journal=Anesthesiology|volume=111|issue=1|pages=209\u2013210|doi=10.1097/aln.0b013e3181a8617e|pmid=19546703|issn=0003-3022}}</ref> It is also still used as a sedative prior to [[Electroencephalography|EEG]] procedures, as it is one of the few available sedatives that does not suppress [[epilepsy|epileptiform]] discharges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jcc.kau.edu.sa/Files/140/Researches/11822_Chloral.pdf|title=The use of chloral hydrate in pediatric electroencephalography|author1=Mohammed M.S. Jan, MBChB, FRCP (C)|author2=Marilou F. Aquino, EEG Tech.|website=Jcc.kau.edu.sa|accessdate=15 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818213222/http://jcc.kau.edu.sa/Files/140/Researches/11822_Chloral.pdf|archive-date=18 August 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn therapeutic doses for insomnia, chloral hydrate is effective within 20 to 60 minutes.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Chloral hydrate: a hypnotic best forgotten? |last1=Gauillard |first1=J. |last2=Cheref |first2=S. |last3=Vacherontrystram |first3=M. N. |first4=Martin |last4=J. C. | journal=Encephale |date=May\u2013June 2002 | volume=28 | issue=3 Pt 1 | pages=200\u2013204 | pmid=12091779}}</ref> In humans it is [[Metabolism|metabolized]] within 7 hours into [[trichloroethanol]] and trichloroethanol glucuronide by erythrocytes and plasma esterases and into [[trichloroacetic acid]] in 4 to 5 days.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ntp.niehs.nih.gov/ntp/htdocs/st_rpts/tox059.pdf | title=NTP Technical Report on the Toxicity and Metabolism Studies of Chloral Hydrate | publisher=National Toxicology Program | work=Toxicity Report Series Number 59 | accessdate=14 March 2013 | last=Beland | first=Frederick A. | pages=10}}</ref> It has a very narrow therapeutic window making this drug difficult to use. Higher doses can depress [[Respiration (physiology)|respiration]] and [[blood pressure]].\n\n===In organic synthesis===\nChloral hydrate is a starting point for the synthesis of other organic compounds. It is the starting material for the production of [[chloral]], which is produced by the distillation of a mixture of chloral hydrate and [[sulfuric acid]], which serves as the [[desiccant]].\n\nNotably, it is used to synthesize [[isatin]]. In this synthesis, chloral hydrate reacts with [[aniline]] and [[hydroxylamine]] to give a condensation product which cyclicizes in [[sulfuric acid]] to give the target compound:<ref>{{OrgSynth | title = Isatin | first1 = C. S. | last1 = Marvel | first2 = G. S. | last2 = Hiers | collvol = 1 | collvolpages = 327 | year = 1941 | prep = cv1p0327}}</ref>\n\n:[[File:Synthesis of isatin.svg|450px]]\n\nMoreover, chloral hydrate is used as a reagent for the deprotection of acetals, dithioacetals and tetrahydropyranyl ethers in organic solvents.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chandrasekhar |first1=S. |last2=Shrinidhi |first2=A. |title=Chloral Hydrate as a Water Carrier for the Efficient Deprotection of Acetals, Dithioacetals, and Tetrahydropyranyl Ethers in Organic Solvents |journal=Synthetic Communications |date=2014 |volume=44 |issue=13 |pages=1904\u20131913 |doi=10.1080/00397911.2013.876652}}</ref>\n\n===Botany and mycology===\n====Hoyer's mounting medium====\nChloral hydrate is also an ingredient used for Hoyer's solution, a [[mounting medium]] for microscopic observation of diverse plant types such as [[bryophyte]]s, [[fern]]s, [[seed]]s, and small [[arthropod]]s (especially [[mite]]s). Other ingredients may include [[gum arabic]] and [[glycerol]]. An advantage of this medium includes a high [[refractive index]] and clearing (macerating) properties of small specimens (especially advantageous if specimens require observation with [[differential interference contrast microscopy]]).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n====Melzer's reagent====\nChloral hydrate is an ingredient used to make [[Melzer's reagent]], an [[aqueous solution]] that is used to identify certain species of [[fungi]]. The other ingredients are [[potassium iodide]], and [[iodine]]. Whether tissue or spores react to this reagent is vital for the correct identification of some mushrooms.\n\n==Safety==\nChloral hydrate was routinely administered in gram quantities. Prolonged exposure to the vapors is unhealthy however, with a [[Median lethal dose|LD<sub>50</sub>]] for 4-hour exposure of 440&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>. Long-term use of chloral hydrate is associated with a rapid development of tolerance to its effects and possible addiction as well as adverse effects including rashes, gastric discomfort and severe kidney, heart, and liver failure.<ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Gelder | first1 = M. | last2 = Mayou | first2 = R. | last3 = Geddes | first3 = J. | year = 2005 | title = Psychiatry | edition = 3rd | location = New York | publisher = Oxford | page = 238}}</ref>\n\nAcute overdosage is often characterized by [[nausea]], vomiting, confusion, [[convulsion]]s, slow and irregular breathing, [[cardiac arrhythmia]], and [[coma]]. The [[Blood plasma|plasma]], [[Blood serum|serum]] or [[blood]] concentrations of chloral hydrate and/or trichloroethanol, its major active metabolite, may be measured to confirm a diagnosis of poisoning in hospitalized patients or to aid in the medicolegal investigation of fatalities. Accidental [[Drug overdose|overdosage]] of young children undergoing simple dental or surgical procedures has occurred. [[Hemodialysis]] has been used successfully to accelerate clearance of the drug in poisoning victims.<ref>{{Cite book | first = R. | last = Baselt | title = Disposition of Toxic Drugs and Chemicals in Man | edition = 8th | publisher = Biomedical Publications | location = Foster City, CA | year = 2008 | pages = 259\u2013261}}</ref> It is listed as having a \"conditional risk\" of causing [[torsades de pointes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crediblemeds.org/index.php/drugsearch|title=CredibleMeds :: Quicksearch|website=Crediblemeds.org|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nChloral hydrate is produced from [[chlorine]] and [[ethanol]] in acidic solution. In basic conditions the [[haloform reaction]] takes place and chloral hydrate is [[Chemical decomposition|decomposed]] by [[hydrolysis]] to form [[chloroform]].<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://jhs.pharm.or.jp/data/49%281%29/49_1.pdf | title=A Problem in the Determination of Trihalomethane by Headspace-Gas Chromatography/Mass Spectrometry |last1=Takahashi |first1=Yasuo |last2=Onodera |first2=Sukeo |last3=Morita |first3=Masatoshi |last4=Terao |first4=Yoshiyasu | journal=Journal of Health Science | year=2003 | volume=49 | issue=1 | pages=3 | doi=10.1248/jhs.49.1}}</ref>\n\n:4&nbsp;Cl<sub>2</sub> + C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub>OH + H<sub>2</sub>O \u2192 Cl<sub>3</sub>CCH(OH)<sub>2</sub> + 5&nbsp;HCl\n\n==Pharmacology==\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nChloral hydrate is metabolized ''[[in vivo]]'' to [[trichloroethanol]], which is responsible for secondary physiological and psychological effects.<ref name=Ull>{{Ullmann|first1=Reinhard |last1=Jira |first2=Erwin |last2=Kopp |first3=Blaine C. |last3=McKusick |first4=Gerhard |last4=R\u00f6derer |first5=Axel |last5=Bosch |first6=Gerald |last6=Fleischmann |title=Chloroacetaldehydes |doi=10.1002/14356007.a06_527.pub2}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate is structurally and [[pharmacodynamics | pharmacodynamically]] similar to [[ethchlorvynol]] (Placidyl), a pharmaceutical developed during the 1950s that was marketed as a hypnotic until 1999 when production was voluntarily ceased by manufacturers in favor of benzodiazepines. The metabolite of chloral hydrate exerts its pharmacological properties via enhancing the [[GABA receptor]] complex<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=17557503 |year=2006 |last1=Lu |first1=J. |last2=Greco |first2=M. A. |title=Sleep circuitry and the hypnotic mechanism of GABA<sub>A</sub> drugs |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=S19\u2013S26 |journal=Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine}}</ref> and therefore is similar in action to [[benzodiazepine]]s, [[nonbenzodiazepines]] and [[barbiturates]]. It can be moderately [[Substance use disorder|addictive]], as [[chronic (medicine)|chronic]] use is known to cause [[Chemical dependency|dependency]] and [[Drug withdrawal|withdrawal]] symptoms. The chemical can potentiate various [[anticoagulant]]s and is weakly [[mutagen]]ic ''[[in vitro]]'' and ''in vivo''.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}}\n\n==Legal status==\nIn the United States, chloral hydrate is a [[Controlled Substances Act#Schedule_IV_controlled_substances|schedule IV]] [[controlled substance]] and requires a physician's prescription. Its properties have sometimes led to its use as a [[date rape drug]].<ref name=\"pmid15622794\">{{cite journal |last1= McGregor |first1=M. J. |last2=Ericksen |first2=J. |last3=Ronald |first3=L. A. |last4=Janssen |first4=P. A. |last5=Van Vliet |first5=A. |last6=Schulzer |first6=M. |title=Rising incidence of hospital-reported drug-facilitated sexual assault in a large urban community in Canada. Retrospective population-based study |journal=Canadian Journal of Public Health |volume=95 |issue=6 |pages=441\u2013445 |year=2004 |pmid=15622794 |doi= 10.1007/BF03403990|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/attacked-gang-article-1.305483|title=Attacked by the Gang|website = New York Daily News|date= 25 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nChloral hydrate was first synthesized by the chemist [[Justus von Liebig]] in 1832 at the University of Giessen.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=A History of Psychiatry: From the era of the asylum to the age of Prozac|first=Edward|last=Shorter|date=1998|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-0471245315|oclc=60169541}}</ref> Through experimentation physiologist [[Claude Bernard]] clarified that the chloral hydrate was [[hypnotic]] as opposed to an [[analgesic]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Worst of Evils: The fight against pain|first=Thomas|last=Dormandy|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300113228|oclc=878623979|url=https://archive.org/details/worstofevilsmans00dorm}}</ref> It was the first of a long line of sedatives, most notably the [[barbiturate]]s, manufactured and marketed by the German pharmaceutical industry.<ref name=\":0\" /> Historically, chloral hydrate was utilized primarily as a [[psychiatric medication]]. In 1869, German physician and pharmacologist [[Oscar Liebreich]] began to promote its use to calm anxiety, especially when it caused insomnia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Before Prozac: The troubled history of mood disorders in psychiatry|first=Edward|last=Shorter|date=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195368741|oclc=299368559|url=https://archive.org/details/beforeprozactrou00shor}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Chloral hydrate had certain advantages over [[morphine]] for this application, as it worked quickly without injection and had a consistent strength. It achieved wide use in both [[Lunatic asylum|asylums]] and the homes of those socially refined enough to avoid asylums. Upper- and middle-class women, well-represented in the latter category, were particularly susceptible to chloral hydrate [[addiction]]. After the 1904 invention of [[barbital]], the first of the [[barbiturate]] family, chloral hydrate began to disappear from use among those with means.<ref name=\":0\" /> It remained common in asylums and hospitals until the Second World War as it was quite cheap. Chloral hydrate had some other important advantages that kept it in use for five decades despite the existence of more advanced [[barbiturate]]s. It was the safest available sedative until the middle of the twentieth century, and thus was particularly favored for children.<ref name=\":1\" /> It also left patients much more refreshed after a deep sleep than more recently invented sedatives. Its frequency of use made it an early and regular feature in ''[[The Merck Manuals|The Merck Manual]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuadrado|first=Fernando F.|last2=Alston|first2=Theodore A.|date=October 2016|title=Book Review|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=4|pages=153\u2013155|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2016.01.004|issn=2352-4529}}</ref>\n\nChloral hydrate was also a significant object of study in various early pharmacological experiments. In 1875, [[Claude Bernard]] tried to determine if chloral hydrate exerted its action through a metabolic conversion to [[chloroform]]. This was not only the first attempt to determine whether different drugs were converted to the same [[metabolite]] in the body but also the first to measure the concentration of a particular pharmaceutical in the blood. The results were inconclusive.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alston|first=Theodore A.|date=July 2016|title=Noteworthy Chemistry of Chloroform|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=3|pages=85\u201388|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2016.04.008|pmid=27480474|issn=2352-4529}}</ref> In 1899 and 1901 [[Hans Horst Meyer]] and [[Ernest Overton]] respectively made the major discovery that the [[Theories of general anaesthetic action|general anaesthetic action]] of a drug was strongly correlated to its [[lipid]] [[solubility]]. However, chloral hydrate was quite polar but nonetheless a potent hypnotic. Overton was unable to explain this mystery. Thus, chloral hydrate remained one of the major and persistent exceptions to this breakthrough discovery in pharmacology. This anomaly was eventually resolved in 1948, when Claude Bernard's experiment was repeated. While chloral hydrate was converted to a different metabolite than chloroform, it was found that was converted into the more [[lipophilic]] molecule [[2,2,2-Trichloroethanol]]. This metabolite fit much better with the Meyer\u2013Overton correlation than chloral had. Prior to this, it had not been demonstrated that general anesthetics could undergo chemical changes to exert their action in the body.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krasowski|first=Matthew D.|title=Contradicting a Unitary Theory of General Anesthetic Action: a History of Three Compounds from 1901 to 2001|journal=Bulletin of Anesthesia History|language=en|volume=21|issue=3|pages=1\u201324|doi=10.1016/s1522-8649(03)50031-2|pmid=17494361|pmc=2701367|year=2003}}</ref>\n\nFinally, chloral hydrate was also the first hypnotic to be used [[intravenous injection|intravenously]] as a general anesthetic. In 1871, [[Pierre-Cyprien Or\u00e9]] began experiments on animals, followed by humans. While a state of general anesthesia could be achieved, the technique never caught on because its administration was more complex and less safe than the oral administration of chloral hydrate, and less safe for intravenous use than later general anesthetics were found to be.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Matthew|last2=Jagdish|first2=S.|date=January 2016|title=A History of Intravenous Anesthesia in War (1656\u20131988)|url=http://www.anesthesiahistoryjournal.org/article/S2352-4529(15)00084-5/fulltext|journal=Journal of Anesthesia History|language=English|volume=2|issue=1|pages=13\u201321|doi=10.1016/j.janh.2015.10.007|pmid=26898141|issn=2352-4529}}</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\nChloral hydrate was used as one of the earliest synthetic drugs to treat [[insomnia]] until 1912, when [[phenobarbital]] replaced it and made its use unnecessary.\n\nIn 1897, [[Bram Stoker]]'s [[epistolary novel]] ''[[Dracula]]'', one of its characters, Doctor [[John Seward]], recorded his use and his [[molecular formula]] in his [[phonograph]]ic [[diary]]:\n\n<blockquote>I cannot but think of Lucy, and how different things might have been. If I don't sleep at once, chloral, the modern [[Morpheus]]\u2014 C<sub>2</sub>HCl<sub>3</sub>O&nbsp;.&nbsp;H<sub>2</sub>O! I should be careful not to let it grow into a habit. No I shall take none to-night! I have thought of Lucy, and I shall not dishonor her by mixing the two.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/draculabr00stokuoft|title=Dracula|first=Bram|last=Stoker|date=28 February 1897|publisher=New York Grosset & Dunlap|accessdate=28 February 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the conclusion of [[Edith Wharton]]'s 1905 novel ''[[The House of Mirth]]'', Lily Bart, the novel's heroine, becomes addicted to chloral hydrate and overdoses on the substance:\n<blockquote>She put out her hand and measured the soothing drops into a glass; but as she did so, she knew they would be powerless against the supernatural lucidity of her brain. She had long since raised the dose to its highest limit, but to-night she felt she must increase it. She knew she took a slight risk in doing so; she remembered the chemist's warning. If sleep came at all, it might be a sleep without waking.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/284/284-h/284-h.htm#chap0213|title=House of Mirth|website=www.gutenberg.org|access-date=2 July 2018|date=June 1995}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the third season of the HBO drama series ''[[Oz]]'', the drug is used by inmate [[Ryan O'Reily]] to aid his brother, [[Cyril O'Reily]], during a boxing tournament by sneaking the drug into his opponent's drinking bottles, slowing the fighter down and allowing for Cyril to win his fights.\n\n==Notable users==\n*[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]] (1828\u20131882) became addicted to chloral, with whisky chasers, after the death of his wife [[Elizabeth Siddal]] from a [[laudanum]] overdose in 1862. He had a mental breakdown in 1872. He lived out the last ten years of his life addicted to chloral and alcohol, in part to mask the pain of botched surgery to an enlarged testicle in 1877.\n* Irish physicist [[John Tyndall]] (1820\u20131893) died of an accidental overdose of chloral administered by his wife.\n* Psychologist and philosopher [[William James]] (1842-1910) who used the drug for insomnia and sedation due to chronic neurosis.\n* [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] (1844\u20131900) regularly used chloral hydrate in the years leading up to his nervous breakdown, according to Lou Salome and other associates. Whether the drug contributed to his insanity is a point of controversy.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cate |first=Curtis |title=Friedrich Nietzsche |publisher=[[The Overlook Press]] |year=2005 |place=Woodstock, NY|ref=harv|page=453}}</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Gide]] (1869\u20131951) was given chloral hydrate as a boy for sleep problems by a physician named Lizart. Gide states in his autobiography ''[[Si le grain ne meurt|If It Die...]]'' that \"all my later weaknesses of will or memory I attribute to him.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Gide|first=Andr\u00e9|authorlink=Andr\u00e9 Gide|translator-first=Dorothy|translator-last=Bussey|title=If It Die...An Autobiography|location=New York|publisher=Vintage International|orig-year=1924|date=2001|page=105}}</ref>\n*[[Evelyn Waugh]] (1903-1966), insomniac for much of his adult life, for which 'in later life ... he became so deleteriously dependent on chloral'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hastings|first=Selina|title=Evelyn Waugh: A Biography|publisher=Sinclair-Stevenson|year=1994|isbn=1 85619 223 7|location=|pages=140}}</ref>  Waugh's novel, ''[[The Ordeal of Gilbert Pinfold]]'', is largely a fictionalised account of an episode Waugh himself experienced as a result of excessive use of chloral in combination with bromide and alcohol.  Waugh's friend and biographer [[Christopher Sykes (author)|Christopher Sykes]] observed that Waugh's description of [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti|D.G. Rossetti]]'s demise under the effects of excessive use of chloral in his 1928 biography of the artist 'is a fairly exact description of how [Waugh's own] life ended in 1966'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sykes|first=Christopher|title=Evelyn Waugh: A Biography|publisher=Penguin Books|year=1977|isbn=|location=|pages=124}}</ref>\n* [[Marilyn Monroe]] (1926\u20131962) died from an overdose of chloral hydrate and [[pentobarbital]] (Nembutal).<ref>{{Cite book | last = Banner | first = Lois | title = Marilyn: The Passion and the Paradox | year = 2012 | publisher = Bloomsbury | isbn = 978-1-40883-133-5 | pages = [https://archive.org/details/marilynpassionpa0000bann/page/411 411\u2013412] | url = https://archive.org/details/marilynpassionpa0000bann/page/411 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last=Spoto | first=Donald | title=Marilyn Monroe: The Biography | publisher=Cooper Square Press | year=2001 | isbn=978-0-8154-1183-3 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/marilynmonroe00dona/page/580 580\u2013583] | url=https://archive.org/details/marilynmonroe00dona/page/580 }}</ref>\n* [[Oliver Sacks]] (1933\u20132015) abused chloral hydrate in 1965 as a depressed insomniac. He found himself taking fifteen times the usual dose of chloral hydrate every night before he eventually ran out, causing violent withdrawal symptoms.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sacks|first=Oliver|title=Altered States|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/08/27/altered-states-3 |work=The New Yorker |date=27 August 2012|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Jonestown|The Jonestown mass murder-suicides]] in 1978, involved the communal drinking of [[Flavor Aid]] poisoned with [[diazepam|Valium]], chloral hydrate, [[potassium cyanide|cyanide]], and [[Phenergan]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hall|first1=John R.|title=Gone from the Promised Land: Jonestown in American Cultural History|date=1987|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=9780887388019|page=282|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D8MCb1xqqo8C&pg=PA282|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Hank Williams]] (1923\u20131953) died from a combination of chloral hydrate, [[morphine]] and [[whiskey]].<ref>{{Harvnb|\n Olson, Ted |2004|p= 296}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb| Olson, Ted| 2004| p= 298}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |author= Lilly, John|title= Hank's Lost Charleston Show|publisher= West Virginia Division of Culture and History}}</ref>\n* [[Montgomery Clift]]<ref>Brando, Marlon; Lindsey, Robert (1994). Songs my mother taught me. New York: Random House. {{ISBN|978-0-09-943691-1}}.</ref>\n* [[Anna Nicole Smith]] (1967\u20132007) died of \"[[combined drug intoxication]]\" with [[chloral hydrate]] as the \"major component.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070326/ap_on_en_tv/anna_nicole_smith |title=Smith died from accidental drug overdose |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070331213201/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070326/ap_on_en_tv/anna_nicole_smith |archivedate=31 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chlorobutanol]]\n* [[Disulfiram-like drug]]\n* [[Trichloroethanol]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Chloral hydrate}}\n\n{{Sedative|state=collapsed}}\n{{GABAAR PAMs}}\n{{Glycinergics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chloral Hydrate}}\n[[Category:Acetaldehyde dehydrogenase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Aldehydes]]\n[[Category:GABAA receptor positive allosteric modulators]]\n[[Category:Glycine receptor agonists]]\n[[Category:Hydrates]]\n[[Category:Hypnotics]]\n[[Category:Sedatives]]\n[[Category:Organochlorides]]\n[[Category:Prodrugs]]\n[[Category:Trichloromethyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Geminal diols]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toOz(link changed toOz (TV series)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloral_hydrate"}
{"title_page": "The Patchwork Girl of Oz", "text_new": "{{short description|Book}}\n{{Infobox book | \n| name          = The Patchwork Girl of Oz\n| image         = File:ThePatchworkGirlOfOz.jpg\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[L. Frank Baum]]\n| illustrator   = [[John R. Neill]]\n|cover_artist   = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = [[List of Oz books|The Oz books]]\n| genre         = [[Children's literature|Children's novel]]\n| publisher     = [[Reilly & Britton]]\n| release_date  = 1913\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover)\n| preceded_by   = [[The Emerald City of Oz]]<!-- preceding novel in series -->\n| followed_by   = [[Tik-Tok of Oz]]<!-- following novel in series -->\n}}\n\n'''''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''''' by [[L. Frank Baum]] is a children's novel, the seventh in the [[Oz series]]. Characters include the [[List of Oz characters#Woozy|Woozy]], [[Ojo the Lucky|Ojo]] \"the Unlucky\", [[List of Oz characters#Unc Nunkie|Unc Nunkie]], [[List of Oz characters#Dr. Pipt|Dr. Pipt]], [[List of Oz characters#Patchwork Girl|Scraps]] (the patchwork girl), and others. The book was first published on July 1, 1913, with illustrations by [[John R. Neill]]. In 1914, Baum adapted the book to film through his \"[[Oz Film Manufacturing Company]].\"\n\nIn the previous Oz book, ''[[The Emerald City of Oz]]'', [[magic (paranormal)|magic]] was used to isolate Oz from all contact with the outside world. Baum did this to end the Oz series, but was forced to restart the series with this book due to financial hardship.<ref>{{harvnb|Riley|1997|page=171}}</ref> In the prologue, he reconciles Oz's isolation with the appearance of a new Oz book by explaining that he contacted [[Dorothy Gale|Dorothy]] in Oz via [[wireless telegraphy]], and she obtained Ozma's permission to tell Baum this story.<ref>{{harvnb|Riley|1997|page=176}}</ref> \n\nThe book was dedicated to Sumner Hamilton Britton, the young son of one of its publishers, Sumner Charles Britton of [[Reilly & Britton]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[Ojo the Lucky|Ojo]], known as Ojo the Unlucky, lives in poverty with his laconic uncle [[Unc Nunkie]] in the woods of the [[Munchkin Country]] in [[Land of Oz|Oz]]. They visit their neighbor, the magician [[List of Oz characters#Dr. Pipt|Dr. Pipt]] who is about to complete the six-year process of preparing the magical Powder of Life, which can bring inanimate objects to life. Pipt's wife has constructed a life-sized stuffed girl out of [[patchwork]], and wishes her husband to animate her to serve as an obedient household servant. They also meet another of Pipt's creations, Bungle, an extremely vain talking cat made of glass. The Powder of Life successfully animates the patchwork girl, but an accident causes both Pipt's wife and Unc Nunkie to be turned to stone. Dr. Pipt tells Ojo that he must obtain five ingredients to make a compound to counteract the petrifaction spell.\n\nOjo and the patchwork girl, who calls herself Scraps, along with Bungle, embark on a journey to obtain the magic ingredients: a six-leaved clover, the wing of a yellow butterfly, water from a dark well, a drop of oil from a live man's body, and three hairs from a Woozy's tail. Scraps exhibits a wild, carefree personality, and is prone to spontaneous recitation of nonsense poetry. After several adventures, they meet a Woozy, a blocky quadruped who agrees to let them have three hairs from its tail. But they are unable to remove the hairs, so they take the Woozy along with them.\n\nThe party is captured by large animate plants, but they are rescued by the fortuitous arrival of the [[Shaggy Man]]. He leads them to the [[Emerald City]] to meet [[Ozma]], but warns Ojo that picking a six-leaved clover is forbidden by law in Oz. Along the way they meet the [[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]], who is quite smitten with Scraps, as she is with him. Just outside the Emerald City, Ojo sees a six-leaved clover by the road and, believing himself to be unobserved, picks it. When they arrive at the city gates, the [[Soldier with the Green Whiskers]] approaches them and announces that Ojo is under arrest.\n\nBrought to trial before Ozma, Ojo confesses and Ozma pardons him and allows him to keep the clover. [[Dorothy Gale|Dorothy]] and the Scarecrow join Ojo and Scraps as they continue their search for the remaining ingredients. Along the way they meet [[Jack Pumpkinhead]], the playful but annoying Tottenhots, and the man-eating 21-foot-tall giant [[List of Oz characters (created by Baum)#Mr. Yoop|Mr. Yoop]], before reaching the subterranean dwellings of the Hoppers, who each have just one leg, and the neighboring Horners, who each have one horn on their head. The two groups are on the verge of war due to a misunderstanding, but Scraps reconciles them. A grateful Horner leads the group to a well in a dark [[radium]] mine, and Ojo collects a flask of water from it.\n\nThe group continues to the castle of the [[Tin Woodsman]] who rules the [[Winkie Country]], since yellow butterflies are most likely to be found in that yellow-dominated quadrant of Oz. While talking to the Tin Woodsman, Ojo notices a drop of oil about to drip from his body, and he catches it in a vial. He explains that he now has all the ingredients except one. But when he describes the last one, the Tin Woodsman is horrified at the idea of killing an innocent butterfly, and forbids them from doing so in his realm. Ojo is devastated, but the Tin Woodsman proposes that they all travel back to the Emerald City to ask Ozma's advice.\n\nOzma tells them that Dr. Pipt has been practicing magic illegally and has therefore been deprived of his powers. But the petrified Unc Nunkie and Pipt's wife have been brought to the Emerald City and as they all watch, the [[Wizard of Oz]] restores them to life. Ojo and Unc Nunkie are given a new house to live in near the Emerald City and the Tin Woodsman calls Ojo \"Ojo the Lucky\".\n\n==Background and analysis==\nIn reference to ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz,'' one of Baum's letters to his publisher, Sumner Britton of [[Reilly & Britton]], offers unusual insight on Baum's manner of creating his Oz fantasies:\n\n{{quote|\nA lot of thought is required on one of these fairy tales. The odd characters are a sort of inspiration, liable to strike me at any time, but the plot and plan of adventures takes me considerable time...I live with it day by day, jotting down on odd slips of paper the various ideas that occur and in this way getting my materials together. The new Oz book is at this stage....But...it's a long way from being ready for the printer yet. I must rewrite it, stringing the incidents into consecutive order, elaborating the characters, etc. Then it's typewritten. Then it's revised, retypewritten and sent on to Reilly and Britton.<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|pages=179\u201380}}</ref>}}\n\nThe same correspondence (November 23\u20137, 1912) discusses the deleted Chapter 21 of the book, \"The Garden of Meats.\" The text of the chapter has not survived, but Neill's illustrations and their captions still exist. The deleted chapter dealt with a race of vegetable people comparable to the Mangaboos in Chapters 4\u20136 of ''[[Dorothy and the Wizard in Oz]].'' The vegetable people grow what Baum elsewhere calls \"meat people,\" apparently for food; Neill's pictures show plants with the heads of human children<ref>Bodiless human heads are rather a pre-occupation with Baum; they occur repeatedly in his fantasies, ''Ozma of Oz'', Chapter 6 and ''The Tin Woodman of Oz,'' Chapter 18 being two examples.</ref> being watered by their growers. (This is thematically connected with the anthropophagous plants in Chapter 10 of ''Patchwork Girl.'') Frank Reilly tactfully wrote to Baum that the material was not \"in harmony with your other fairy stories,\" and would generate \"considerable adverse criticism.\" Baum saw his point; the chapter was dropped.<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|pages=198\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAt least at one point in his life, Baum stated that he considered ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz'' \"one of the two best books of my career\", the other being ''[[The Sea Fairies]].''<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|page=184}}</ref> The book was a popular success, selling just over 17,000 copies\u2014though this was somewhat lower than the total for the previous book, ''The Emerald City of Oz,'' and marked the start of a trend in declining sales for the Oz books that would not reverse until ''[[The Tin Woodman of Oz]]'' in 1918.\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{See also|The Patchwork Girl of Oz (1914 film)}}\nBaum also wrote a musical stage adaptation of the book, circa 1913, with composer [[Louis F. Gottschalk]]; however, this musical was never staged. Excerpts have occasionally been performed at various annual conventions of [[The International Wizard of Oz Club]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=Michael O.|last=Riley|title=Oz and Beyond: The Fantasy World of L. Frank Baum|isbn=0-7006-0832-X|date=1997|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rogers|first=Katharine M.|date=2002|title=L. Frank Baum, Creator of Oz|publisher=Macmillan|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource4|the complete text of|[[:wikisource:The Patchwork Girl of Oz|The Patchwork Girl of Oz]]}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature|Novels}}\n* {{gutenberg|no=955|name=The Patchwork Girl of Oz}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/patchworkgirlofo00baum ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''] at [[Internet Archive]]\n* {{librivox book | title=The Patchwork Girl of Oz | author=L. Frank Baum}}\n* {{OL work|id=20526996W|cname=''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''}}\n\n{{Oz books|\nbefore=The Emerald City of Oz|\nafter=Tik-Tok of Oz|\ntitle=The Patchwork Girl of Oz|\nyear=1913}}\n\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patchwork Girl of Oz}}\n[[Category:Oz (franchise) books]]\n[[Category:1913 American novels]]\n[[Category:1913 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Sequel novels]]\n[[Category:Books about cats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Book}}\n{{Infobox book | \n| name          = The Patchwork Girl of Oz\n| image         = File:ThePatchworkGirlOfOz.jpg\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[L. Frank Baum]]\n| illustrator   = [[John R. Neill]]\n|cover_artist   = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = [[List of Oz books|The Oz books]]\n| genre         = [[Children's literature|Children's novel]]\n| publisher     = [[Reilly & Britton]]\n| release_date  = 1913\n| media_type    = Print (hardcover)\n| preceded_by   = [[The Emerald City of Oz]]<!-- preceding novel in series -->\n| followed_by   = [[Tik-Tok of Oz]]<!-- following novel in series -->\n}}\n\n'''''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''''' by [[L. Frank Baum]] is a children's novel, the seventh in the [[Oz series]]. Characters include the [[List of Oz characters#Woozy|Woozy]], [[Ojo the Lucky|Ojo]] \"the Unlucky\", [[List of Oz characters#Unc Nunkie|Unc Nunkie]], [[List of Oz characters#Dr. Pipt|Dr. Pipt]], [[List of Oz characters#Patchwork Girl|Scraps]] (the patchwork girl), and others. The book was first published on July 1, 1913, with illustrations by [[John R. Neill]]. In 1914, Baum adapted the book to film through his \"[[Oz Film Manufacturing Company]].\"\n\nIn the previous Oz book, ''[[The Emerald City of Oz]]'', [[magic (paranormal)|magic]] was used to isolate Oz from all contact with the outside world. Baum did this to end the Oz series, but was forced to restart the series with this book due to financial hardship.<ref>{{harvnb|Riley|1997|page=171}}</ref> In the prologue, he reconciles Oz's isolation with the appearance of a new Oz book by explaining that he contacted [[Dorothy Gale|Dorothy]] in Oz via [[wireless telegraphy]], and she obtained Ozma's permission to tell Baum this story.<ref>{{harvnb|Riley|1997|page=176}}</ref> \n\nThe book was dedicated to Sumner Hamilton Britton, the young son of one of its publishers, Sumner Charles Britton of [[Reilly & Britton]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[Ojo the Lucky|Ojo]], known as Ojo the Unlucky, lives in poverty with his laconic uncle [[Unc Nunkie]] in the woods of the [[Munchkin Country]] in [[Oz]]. They visit their neighbor, the magician [[List of Oz characters#Dr. Pipt|Dr. Pipt]] who is about to complete the six-year process of preparing the magical Powder of Life, which can bring inanimate objects to life. Pipt's wife has constructed a life-sized stuffed girl out of [[patchwork]], and wishes her husband to animate her to serve as an obedient household servant. They also meet another of Pipt's creations, Bungle, an extremely vain talking cat made of glass. The Powder of Life successfully animates the patchwork girl, but an accident causes both Pipt's wife and Unc Nunkie to be turned to stone. Dr. Pipt tells Ojo that he must obtain five ingredients to make a compound to counteract the petrifaction spell.\n\nOjo and the patchwork girl, who calls herself Scraps, along with Bungle, embark on a journey to obtain the magic ingredients: a six-leaved clover, the wing of a yellow butterfly, water from a dark well, a drop of oil from a live man's body, and three hairs from a Woozy's tail. Scraps exhibits a wild, carefree personality, and is prone to spontaneous recitation of nonsense poetry. After several adventures, they meet a Woozy, a blocky quadruped who agrees to let them have three hairs from its tail. But they are unable to remove the hairs, so they take the Woozy along with them.\n\nThe party is captured by large animate plants, but they are rescued by the fortuitous arrival of the [[Shaggy Man]]. He leads them to the [[Emerald City]] to meet [[Ozma]], but warns Ojo that picking a six-leaved clover is forbidden by law in Oz. Along the way they meet the [[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]], who is quite smitten with Scraps, as she is with him. Just outside the Emerald City, Ojo sees a six-leaved clover by the road and, believing himself to be unobserved, picks it. When they arrive at the city gates, the [[Soldier with the Green Whiskers]] approaches them and announces that Ojo is under arrest.\n\nBrought to trial before Ozma, Ojo confesses and Ozma pardons him and allows him to keep the clover. [[Dorothy Gale|Dorothy]] and the Scarecrow join Ojo and Scraps as they continue their search for the remaining ingredients. Along the way they meet [[Jack Pumpkinhead]], the playful but annoying Tottenhots, and the man-eating 21-foot-tall giant [[List of Oz characters (created by Baum)#Mr. Yoop|Mr. Yoop]], before reaching the subterranean dwellings of the Hoppers, who each have just one leg, and the neighboring Horners, who each have one horn on their head. The two groups are on the verge of war due to a misunderstanding, but Scraps reconciles them. A grateful Horner leads the group to a well in a dark [[radium]] mine, and Ojo collects a flask of water from it.\n\nThe group continues to the castle of the [[Tin Woodsman]] who rules the [[Winkie Country]], since yellow butterflies are most likely to be found in that yellow-dominated quadrant of Oz. While talking to the Tin Woodsman, Ojo notices a drop of oil about to drip from his body, and he catches it in a vial. He explains that he now has all the ingredients except one. But when he describes the last one, the Tin Woodsman is horrified at the idea of killing an innocent butterfly, and forbids them from doing so in his realm. Ojo is devastated, but the Tin Woodsman proposes that they all travel back to the Emerald City to ask Ozma's advice.\n\nOzma tells them that Dr. Pipt has been practicing magic illegally and has therefore been deprived of his powers. But the petrified Unc Nunkie and Pipt's wife have been brought to the Emerald City and as they all watch, the [[Wizard of Oz]] restores them to life. Ojo and Unc Nunkie are given a new house to live in near the Emerald City and the Tin Woodsman calls Ojo \"Ojo the Lucky\".\n\n==Background and analysis==\nIn reference to ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz,'' one of Baum's letters to his publisher, Sumner Britton of [[Reilly & Britton]], offers unusual insight on Baum's manner of creating his Oz fantasies:\n\n{{quote|\nA lot of thought is required on one of these fairy tales. The odd characters are a sort of inspiration, liable to strike me at any time, but the plot and plan of adventures takes me considerable time...I live with it day by day, jotting down on odd slips of paper the various ideas that occur and in this way getting my materials together. The new Oz book is at this stage....But...it's a long way from being ready for the printer yet. I must rewrite it, stringing the incidents into consecutive order, elaborating the characters, etc. Then it's typewritten. Then it's revised, retypewritten and sent on to Reilly and Britton.<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|pages=179\u201380}}</ref>}}\n\nThe same correspondence (November 23\u20137, 1912) discusses the deleted Chapter 21 of the book, \"The Garden of Meats.\" The text of the chapter has not survived, but Neill's illustrations and their captions still exist. The deleted chapter dealt with a race of vegetable people comparable to the Mangaboos in Chapters 4\u20136 of ''[[Dorothy and the Wizard in Oz]].'' The vegetable people grow what Baum elsewhere calls \"meat people,\" apparently for food; Neill's pictures show plants with the heads of human children<ref>Bodiless human heads are rather a pre-occupation with Baum; they occur repeatedly in his fantasies, ''Ozma of Oz'', Chapter 6 and ''The Tin Woodman of Oz,'' Chapter 18 being two examples.</ref> being watered by their growers. (This is thematically connected with the anthropophagous plants in Chapter 10 of ''Patchwork Girl.'') Frank Reilly tactfully wrote to Baum that the material was not \"in harmony with your other fairy stories,\" and would generate \"considerable adverse criticism.\" Baum saw his point; the chapter was dropped.<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|pages=198\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAt least at one point in his life, Baum stated that he considered ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz'' \"one of the two best books of my career\", the other being ''[[The Sea Fairies]].''<ref>{{harvnb|Rogers|2002|page=184}}</ref> The book was a popular success, selling just over 17,000 copies\u2014though this was somewhat lower than the total for the previous book, ''The Emerald City of Oz,'' and marked the start of a trend in declining sales for the Oz books that would not reverse until ''[[The Tin Woodman of Oz]]'' in 1918.\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{See also|The Patchwork Girl of Oz (1914 film)}}\nBaum also wrote a musical stage adaptation of the book, circa 1913, with composer [[Louis F. Gottschalk]]; however, this musical was never staged. Excerpts have occasionally been performed at various annual conventions of [[The International Wizard of Oz Club]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|first=Michael O.|last=Riley|title=Oz and Beyond: The Fantasy World of L. Frank Baum|isbn=0-7006-0832-X|date=1997|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rogers|first=Katharine M.|date=2002|title=L. Frank Baum, Creator of Oz|publisher=Macmillan|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource4|the complete text of|[[:wikisource:The Patchwork Girl of Oz|The Patchwork Girl of Oz]]}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature|Novels}}\n* {{gutenberg|no=955|name=The Patchwork Girl of Oz}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/patchworkgirlofo00baum ''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''] at [[Internet Archive]]\n* {{librivox book | title=The Patchwork Girl of Oz | author=L. Frank Baum}}\n* {{OL work|id=20526996W|cname=''The Patchwork Girl of Oz''}}\n\n{{Oz books|\nbefore=The Emerald City of Oz|\nafter=Tik-Tok of Oz|\ntitle=The Patchwork Girl of Oz|\nyear=1913}}\n\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patchwork Girl of Oz}}\n[[Category:Oz (franchise) books]]\n[[Category:1913 American novels]]\n[[Category:1913 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Sequel novels]]\n[[Category:Books about cats]]\n"